# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ancient-greece
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Initially influenced by Toulouse-Lautrec, Gauguin, and other late-19th-century innovators, Pablo Picasso made his first cubist paintings based on Cézanne's idea that all depiction of nature can be reduced to three solids: cube, sphere, and cone.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] With the painting *Les Demoiselles d'Avignon* (1907; see gallery) Picasso created a new and radical picture depicting a raw and primitive brothel scene with five prostitutes, violently painted women, reminiscent of African tribal masks and his own new proto-Cubist inventions.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Analytic cubism, exemplified by *Violin and Candlestick, Paris*, was jointly developed by Pablo Picasso and Georges Braque from about 1908 through 1912.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Analytic cubism was followed by Synthetic cubism, characterized by the introduction of different textures, surfaces, collage elements, papier collé and a large variety of merged subject matter.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the years between 1910 and the end of World War I and after the heyday of cubism, several movements emerged in Paris.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Giorgio de Chirico moved to Paris in July 1911, where he joined his brother Andrea (the poet and painter known as Alberto Savinio).
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Through his brother he met Pierre Laprade, a member of the jury at the Salon d'Automne, where he exhibited three of his dreamlike works: *Enigma of the Oracle*, *Enigma of an Afternoon* and *Self-Portrait*.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During 1913 he exhibited his work at the Salon des Indépendants and Salon d’Automne, where his work was noticed by Pablo Picasso, Guillaume Apollinaire, and others.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His compelling and mysterious paintings are considered instrumental to the early beginnings of Surrealism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] *Song of Love* (1914) is one of the most famous works by de Chirico and is an early example of the surrealist style, though it was painted ten years before the movement was "founded" by André Breton in 1924.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Modern painting influenced all the visual arts, from Modernist architecture and design, to avant-garde film, theatre and modern dance, and became an experimental laboratory for the expression of visual experience, from photography and concrete poetry to advertising art and fashion.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Van Gogh's paintings exerted great influence upon 20th-century Expressionism, as can be seen in the work of the Fauves, Die Brücke (a group led by German painter Ernst Kirchner), and the Expressionism of Edvard Munch, Egon Schiele, Marc Chagall, Amedeo Modigliani, Chaïm Soutine, and others.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Wassily Kandinsky, a Russian painter, printmaker and art theorist, is generally considered the first important painter of modern abstract art.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As an early modernist, in search of new modes of visual expression, and spiritual expression, he theorized—as did contemporary occultists and theosophists—that pure visual abstraction had corollary vibrations with sound and music.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] They posited that pure abstraction could express pure spirituality.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His earliest abstractions were generally titled (as the example in the above gallery) *Composition VII*, making connection to the work of the composers of music.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Kandinsky included many of his theories about abstract art in his book *Concerning the Spiritual in Art*.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Piet Mondrian's art was also related to his spiritual and philosophical studies.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1908 he became interested in the theosophical movement launched by Helena Petrovna Blavatsky in the late 19th century.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Blavatsky believed that it was possible to attain a knowledge of nature more profound than that provided by empirical means, and much of Mondrian's work for the rest of his life was inspired by his search for that spiritual knowledge.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other major pioneers of early abstraction include Swedish painter Hilma af Klint, Russian painter Kazimir Malevich, and Swiss painter Paul Klee.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Robert Delaunay was a French artist who is associated with Orphism, (reminiscent of a link between pure abstraction and cubism).
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His later works were more abstract, reminiscent of Paul Klee.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His key contributions to abstract painting refer to his bold use of color, and a clear love of experimentation of both depth and tone.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] At the invitation of Kandinsky, Delaunay and his wife the artist Sonia Delaunay, joined The Blue Rider (Der Blaue Reiter), a Munich-based group of abstract artists, in 1911, and his art took a turn to the abstract.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Still other important pioneers of abstract painting include Czech painter, František Kupka as well as American artists Stanton Macdonald-Wright and Morgan Russell who, in 1912, founded Synchromism, an art movement that closely resembles Orphism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Les Fauves (French for *The Wild Beasts*) were early-20th-century painters, experimenting with freedom of expression through color.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The name was given, humorously and not as a compliment, to the group by art critic Louis Vauxcelles.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvism was a short-lived and loose grouping of artists whose works emphasized painterly qualities and the imaginative use of deep color over the representational values.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvists made the subject of the painting easy to read and exaggerated perspectives.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The leaders of the movement were Henri Matisse and André Derain—friendly rivals of a sort, each with his own followers.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Ultimately Matisse became the *yang* to Picasso's *yin* in the 20th century.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvist painters included Albert Marquet, Charles Camoin, Maurice de Vlaminck, Raoul Dufy, Othon Friesz, the Dutch painter Kees van Dongen, and Picasso's partner in Cubism, Georges Braque amongst others.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvism, as a movement, had no concrete theories, and was short lived, beginning in 1905 and ending in 1907.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Matisse was seen as the leader of the movement, due to his seniority in age and prior self-establishment in the academic art world.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Matisse, *The Green Line* (above), caused a sensation in Paris when it was first exhibited.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He said he wanted to create art to delight; art as a decoration was his purpose and it can be said that his use of bright colors tries to maintain serenity of composition.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1906 at the suggestion of his dealer Ambroise Vollard, André Derain went to London and produced a series of paintings like *Charing Cross Bridge, London* (above) in the Fauvist style, paraphrasing the famous series by the Impressionist painter Claude Monet.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] By 1907 Fauvism no longer was a shocking new movement, soon it was replaced by Cubism on the critics radar screen as the latest new development in Contemporary Art of the time.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Der Blaue Reiter was a German movement lasting from 1911 to 1914, fundamental to Expressionism, along with Die Brücke, a group of German expressionist artists formed in Dresden in 1905.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Founding members of Die Brücke were Fritz Bleyl, Erich Heckel, Ernst Ludwig Kirchner and Karl Schmidt-Rottluff.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Later members included Max Pechstein, Otto Mueller and others.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This was a seminal group, which in due course had a major impact on the evolution of modern art in the 20th century and created the style of Expressionism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Der Blaue Reiter lacked a central artistic manifesto, but was centered around Kandinsky and Marc.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists Gabriele Münter and Paul Klee were also involved.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The name of the movement comes from a painting by Kandinsky created in 1903.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is also claimed that the name could have derived from Marc's enthusiasm for horses and Kandinsky's love of the colour blue.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] For Kandinsky, *blue* is the colour of spirituality: the darker the blue, the more it awakens human desire for the eternal.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Marcel Duchamp came to international prominence in the wake of the New York City Armory Show in 1913 where his *Nude Descending a Staircase* became the *cause célèbre*.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He subsequently created *The Bride Stripped Bare by Her Bachelors, Even, Large Glass*.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The *Large Glass* pushed the art of painting to radical new limits being part painting, part collage, part construction.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Duchamp (who was soon to renounce artmaking for chess) became closely associated with the Dada movement that began in neutral Zürich, Switzerland, during World War I and peaked from 1916 to 1920.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The movement primarily involved visual arts, literature (poetry, art manifestoes, art theory), theatre, and graphic design, and concentrated its anti war politic through a rejection of the prevailing standards in art through anti-art cultural works.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Francis Picabia, Man Ray, Kurt Schwitters, Tristan Tzara, Hans Richter, Jean Arp, Sophie Taeuber-Arp, along with Duchamp and many others are associated with the Dadaist movement.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Duchamp and several Dadaists are also associated with Surrealism, the movement that dominated European painting in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1924 André Breton published the *Surrealist Manifesto.* The Surrealist movement in painting became synonymous with the avant-garde and which featured artists whose works varied from the abstract to the super-realist.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] With works on paper like *Machine Turn Quickly* (above) Francis Picabia continued his involvement in the Dada movement through 1919 in Zürich and Paris, before breaking away from it after developing an interest in Surrealist art.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Yves Tanguy, René Magritte and Salvador Dalí are particularly known for their realistic depictions of dream imagery and fantastic manifestations of the imagination.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Joan Miró's *The Tilled Field* of 1923–1924 verges on abstraction, this early painting of a complex of objects and figures, and arrangements of sexually active characters; was Miró's first Surrealist masterpiece.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The more abstract Joan Miró, Jean Arp, André Masson, and Max Ernst were very influential, especially in the United States during the 1940s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Throughout the 1930s, Surrealism continued to become more visible to the public at large.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] A Surrealist group developed in Britain and, according to Breton, their 1936 London International Surrealist Exhibition was a high-water mark of the period and became the model for international exhibitions.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Surrealist groups in Japan, and especially in Latin America, the Caribbean and in Mexico produced innovative and original works.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Dalí and Magritte created some of the most widely recognized images of the movement.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The 1928/1929 painting *This Is Not A Pipe* by Magritte is the subject of a Michel Foucault 1973 book, *This is not a Pipe* (English edition, 1991), that discusses the painting and its paradox.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Dalí joined the group in 1929, and participated in the rapid establishment of the visual style between 1930 and 1935.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Evocations of time and its compelling mystery and absurdity.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Max Ernst studied philosophy and psychology in Bonn and was interested in the alternative realities experienced by the insane.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His paintings, such as *Murdering Airplane* (1920), may have been inspired by the psychoanalyst Sigmund Freud's study of the delusions of a paranoiac, Daniel Paul Schreber.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Freud identified Schreber's fantasy of becoming a woman as a *castration complex*.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The central image of two pairs of legs refers to Schreber's hermaphroditic desires.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Ernst's inscription on the back of the painting reads: *The picture is curious because of its symmetry.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1920s André Masson's work was enormously influential in helping the young artist Joan Miró find his roots in the new Surrealist painting.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Miró acknowledged in letters to his dealer Pierre Matisse the importance of Masson as an example to him in his early years in Paris.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Long after personal, political and professional tensions have fragmented the Surrealist group into thin air and ether, Magritte, Miró, Dalí and the other Surrealists continue to define a visual program in the arts.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other prominent surrealist artists include Giorgio de Chirico, Méret Oppenheim, Toyen, Grégoire Michonze, Roberto Matta, Kay Sage, Leonora Carrington, Dorothea Tanning, and Leonor Fini among others.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1920s and the 1930s and the Great Depression, the European art scene was characterized by Surrealism, late Cubism, the Bauhaus, De Stijl, Dada, Neue Sachlichkeit, and Expressionism; and was occupied by masterful modernist color painters like Henri Matisse and Pierre Bonnard.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Scene painting and the Social Realism and Regionalism movements that contained both political and social commentary dominated the art world in the USA.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists like Ben Shahn, Thomas Hart Benton, Grant Wood, George Tooker, John Steuart Curry, Reginald Marsh, and others became prominent.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Frida Kahlo's Symbolist works also relate strongly to Surrealism and to the Magic Realism movement in literature.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The psychological drama in many of Kahlo's self-portraits (above) underscore the vitality and relevance of her paintings to artists in the 21st century.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Germany Neue Sachlichkeit ("New Objectivity") emerged as Max Beckmann, Otto Dix, George Grosz and others associated with the Berlin Secession politicized their paintings.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The work of these artists grew out of expressionism, and was a response to the political tensions of the Weimar Republic, and was often sharply satirical.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Diego Rivera is perhaps best known by the public for his 1933 mural, *Man at the Crossroads*, in the lobby of the RCA Building at Rockefeller Center.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] When his patron Nelson Rockefeller discovered that the mural included a portrait of Lenin and other communist imagery, he fired Rivera, and the unfinished work was eventually destroyed by Rockefeller's staff.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The film *Cradle Will Rock* includes a dramatization of the controversy.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Frida Kahlo (Rivera's wife's) works are often characterized by their stark portrayals of pain.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Of her 143 paintings 55 are self-portraits, which frequently incorporate symbolic portrayals of her physical and psychological wounds.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Kahlo was deeply influenced by indigenous Mexican culture, which is apparent in her paintings' bright colors and dramatic symbolism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Christian and Jewish themes are often depicted in her work as well; she combined elements of the classic religious Mexican tradition—which were often bloody and violent—with surrealist renderings.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] While her paintings are not overtly Christian—she was an avowed communist—they certainly contain elements of the macabre Mexican Christian style of religious paintings.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1930s radical leftist politics characterized many of the artists connected to Surrealism, including Pablo Picasso.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] On 26 April 1937, during the Spanish Civil War, the Basque town of Gernika was the scene of the "Bombing of Gernika" by the Condor Legion of Nazi Germany's Luftwaffe.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The Germans were attacking to support the efforts of Francisco Franco to overthrow the Basque Government and the Spanish Republican government.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The town was devastated, though the Biscayan assembly and the Oak of Gernika survived.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Picasso painted his mural sized *Guernica* to commemorate the horrors of the bombing.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In its final form, *Guernica* is an immense black and white, 3.5 metre (11 ft) tall and 7.8 metre (23 ft) wide mural painted in oil.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The mural presents a scene of death, violence, brutality, suffering, and helplessness without portraying their immediate causes.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The choice to paint in black and white contrasts with the intensity of the scene depicted and invokes the immediacy of a newspaper photograph.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Picasso painted the mural sized painting called *Guernica* in protest of the bombing.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The painting was first exhibited in Paris in 1937, then Scandinavia, then London in 1938 and finally in 1939 at Picasso's request the painting was sent to the United States in an extended loan (for safekeeping) at MoMA.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The painting went on a tour of museums throughout the U.S. until its final return to the Museum of Modern Art in New York City where it was exhibited for nearly thirty years.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Finally in accord with Picasso's wish to give the painting to the people of Spain as a gift, it was sent to Spain in 1981.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the Great Depression of the 1930s, through the years of World War II American art was characterized by Social Realism and American Scene Painting (as seen above) in the work of Grant Wood, Edward Hopper, Ben Shahn, Thomas Hart Benton, and several others.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] *Nighthawks* (1942) is a painting by Edward Hopper that portrays people sitting in a downtown diner late at night.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is not only Hopper's most famous painting, but one of the most recognizable in American art.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is currently in the collection of the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The scene was inspired by a diner (since demolished) in Greenwich Village, Hopper's home neighborhood in Manhattan.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Hopper began painting it immediately after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] After this event there was a large feeling of gloominess over the country, a feeling that is portrayed in the painting.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The urban street is empty outside the diner, and inside none of the three patrons is apparently looking or talking to the others but instead is lost in their own thoughts.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This portrayal of modern urban life as empty or lonely is a common theme throughout Hopper's work.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The 1940s in New York City heralded the triumph of American abstract expressionism, a modernist movement that combined lessons learned from Henri Matisse, Pablo Picasso, Surrealism, Joan Miró, Cubism, Fauvism, and early Modernism via great teachers in America like Hans Hofmann and John D.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American artists benefited from the presence of Piet Mondrian, Fernand Léger, Max Ernst and the André Breton group, Pierre Matisse's gallery, and Peggy Guggenheim's The Art of This Century Gallery, as well as other factors.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Abstract Expressionism got its name in 1946 from the art critic Robert Coates.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is seen as combining the emotional intensity and self-denial of the German Expressionists with the anti-figurative aesthetic of the European abstract schools such as Futurism, the Bauhaus and Synthetic Cubism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract Expressionism, Action painting, and Color Field painting are synonymous with the New York School.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Technically Surrealism was an important predecessor for Abstract expressionism with its emphasis on spontaneous, automatic or subconscious creation.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Jackson Pollock's dripping paint onto a canvas laid on the floor is a technique that has its roots in the work of André Masson.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Another important early manifestation of what came to be abstract expressionism is the work of American Northwest artist Mark Tobey, especially his "white writing" canvases, which, though generally not large in scale, anticipate the "all over" look of Pollock's drip paintings.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Additionally, abstract expressionism has an image of being rebellious, anarchic, highly idiosyncratic and, some feel, rather nihilistic.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In practice, the term is applied to any number of artists working (mostly) in New York who had quite different styles, and even applied to work which is not especially abstract nor expressionist.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Pollock's energetic "action paintings", with their "busy" feel, are different both technically and aesthetically, to the violent and grotesque *Women* series of Willem de Kooning.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As seen above in the gallery *Woman V* is one of a series of six paintings made by de Kooning between 1950 and 1953 that depict a three-quarter-length female figure.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He began the first of these paintings, *Woman I* collection: The Museum of Modern Art, New York City, in June 1950, repeatedly changing and painting out the image until January or February 1952, when the painting was abandoned unfinished.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The art historian Meyer Schapiro saw the painting in de Kooning's studio soon afterwards and encouraged the artist to persist.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] De Kooning's response was to begin three other paintings on the same theme; *Woman II*, The Museum of Modern Art, New York City, *Woman III*, Tehran Museum of Contemporary Art, *Woman IV*, Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, Kansas City, Missouri.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the summer of 1952, spent at East Hampton, de Kooning further explored the theme through drawings and pastels.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He may have finished work on *Woman I* by the end of June, or possibly as late as November 1952, and probably the other three women pictures were concluded at much the same time.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The *Woman series* are decidedly figurative paintings.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Both Hans Hofmann and Robert Motherwell (gallery) can be comfortably described as practitioners of action painting and Color field painting.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionism has many stylistic similarities to the Russian artists of the early twentieth century such as Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Although it is true that spontaneity or of the impression of spontaneity characterized many of the abstract expressionists works, most of these paintings involved careful planning, especially since their large size demanded it.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] An exception might be the drip paintings of Pollock.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Why this style gained mainstream acceptance in the 1950s is a matter of debate.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Social realism had been the mainstream in the 1930s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It had been influenced not only by the Great Depression but also by the Social Realists of Mexico such as David Alfaro Siqueiros and Diego Rivera.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The political climate after World War II did not long tolerate the social protests of those painters.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionism arose during World War II and began to be showcased during the early 1940s at galleries in New York like The Art of This Century Gallery.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The late 1940s through the mid-1950s ushered in the McCarthy era.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It was after World War II and a time of political conservatism and extreme artistic censorship in the United States.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Some people have conjectured that since the subject matter was often totally abstract, Abstract expressionism became a safe strategy for artists to pursue this style.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract art could be seen as apolitical.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Or if the art was political, the message was largely for the insiders.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] However those theorists are in the minority.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As the first truly original school of painting in America, Abstract expressionism demonstrated the vitality and creativity of the country in the post-war years, as well as its ability (or need) to develop an aesthetic sense that was not constrained by the European standards of beauty.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Although Abstract expressionism spread quickly throughout the United States, the major centers of this style were New York City and California, especially in the New York School, and the San Francisco Bay area.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionist paintings share certain characteristics, including the use of large canvases, an "all-over" approach, in which the whole canvas is treated with equal importance (as opposed to the center being of more interest than the edges).
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The canvas as the *arena* became a credo of Action painting, while the *integrity of the picture plane* became a credo of the Color Field painters.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1950s, Color Field painting initially referred to a particular type of abstract expressionism, especially the work of Mark Rothko, Clyfford Still, Barnett Newman, Robert Motherwell and Adolph Gottlieb.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It essentially involved abstract paintings with large, flat expanses of color that expressed the sensual, and visual feelings and properties of large areas of nuanced surface.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Art critic Clement Greenberg perceived Color Field painting as related to but different from Action painting.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The overall expanse and gestalt of the work of the early color field painters speaks of an almost religious experience, awestruck in the face of an expanding universe of sensuality, color and surface.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists like Clyfford Still, Mark Rothko, Hans Hofmann, Morris Louis, Jules Olitski, Kenneth Noland, Helen Frankenthaler, Larry Zox, and others often used greatly reduced references to nature, and they painted with a highly articulated and psychological use of color.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In general these artists eliminated recognizable imagery.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In *Mountains and Sea,* from 1952, a seminal work of Colorfield painting by Helen Frankenthaler the artist used the stain technique for the first time.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Europe there was the continuation of Surrealism, Cubism, Dada and the works of Matisse.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Also in Europe, Tachisme (the European equivalent to Abstract expressionism) and Informalism took hold of the newest generation.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Serge Poliakoff, Nicolas de Staël, Georges Mathieu, Vieira da Silva, Jean Dubuffet, Yves Klein and Pierre Soulages among others are considered important figures in post-war European painting.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Eventually abstract painting in America evolved into movements such as Neo-Dada, Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, Lyrical Abstraction, Neo-expressionism and the continuation of Abstract expressionism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As a response to the tendency toward abstraction imagery emerged through various new movements, notably Pop art.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1930s through the 1960s as abstract painting in America and Europe evolved into movements such as Abstract Expressionism, Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, and Lyrical abstraction.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other artists reacted as a response to the tendency toward abstraction allowing imagery to continue through various new contexts like the Bay Area Figurative Movement in the 1950s and new forms of expressionism from the 1940s through the 1960s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Italy during this time, Giorgio Morandi was the foremost still life painter, exploring a wide variety of approaches to depicting everyday bottles and kitchen implements.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Throughout the 20th century many painters practiced Realism and used expressive imagery; practicing landscape and figurative painting with contemporary subjects and solid technique, and unique expressivity like Milton Avery, John D.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Graham, Fairfield Porter, Edward Hopper, Andrew Wyeth, Balthus, Francis Bacon, Frank Auerbach, Lucian Freud, Leon Kossoff, Philip Pearlstein, Willem de Kooning, Arshile Gorky, Grace Hartigan, Robert De Niro, Sr., Elaine de Kooning and others.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Along with Henri Matisse, Pablo Picasso, Pierre Bonnard, Georges Braque, and other 20th-century masters.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The figurative work of Francis Bacon, Frida Kahlo, Edward Hopper, Lucian Freud Andrew Wyeth and others served as a kind of alternative to abstract expressionism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] One of the most well-known images in 20th-century American art is Wyeth's painting, *Christina's World*, currently in the collection of the Museum of Modern Art in New York City.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It depicts a woman lying on the ground in a treeless, mostly tawny field, looking up at and crawling towards a gray house on the horizon; a barn and various other small outbuildings are adjacent to the house.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This tempera work, done in a realist style, is nearly always on display at the Museum of Modern Art in New York.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Arshile Gorky's portrait of what may be his friend Willem de Kooning (left) is an example of the evolution of Abstract Expressionism from the context of figure painting, cubism and surrealism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Along with his friends de Kooning and John D.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Graham Gorky created bio-morphically shaped and abstracted figurative compositions that by the 1940s evolved into totally abstract paintings.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Gorky's work seems to be a careful analysis of memory, emotion and shape, using line and color to express feeling and nature.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] After World War II the term School of Paris often referred to Tachisme, the European equivalent of American Abstract expressionism and those artists are also related to Cobra.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1952 Michel Tapié authored the book *Un Autre art* which gave name and voice to Informalism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Important proponents being Jean Dubuffet, Pierre Soulages, Nicolas de Staël, Hans Hartung, Serge Poliakoff, and Georges Mathieu, among several others.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the early 1950s Dubuffet (who was always a figurative artist), and de Staël, abandoned abstraction, and returned to imagery via figuration and landscape.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] De Staël 's work was quickly recognised within the post-war art world, and he became one of the most influential artists of the 1950s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Much of de Staël 's late work – in particular his thinned, and diluted oil on canvas abstract landscapes of the mid-1950s predicts Color Field painting and Lyrical Abstraction of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Nicolas de Staël's bold and intensely vivid color in his last paintings predict the direction of much of contemporary painting that came after him including Pop art of the 1960s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Pop art in America was to a large degree initially inspired by the works of Jasper Johns, Larry Rivers, and Robert Rauschenberg.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Although the paintings of Gerald Murphy, Stuart Davis and Charles Demuth during the 1920s and 1930s set the table for Pop art in America.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In New York City during the mid-1950s Robert Rauschenberg and Jasper Johns created works of art that at first seemed to be continuations of Abstract expressionist painting.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Actually their works and the work of Larry Rivers, were radical departures from abstract expressionism especially in the use of banal and literal imagery and the inclusion and the combining of mundane materials into their work.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Eventually by 1963 the movement came to be known worldwide as Pop art.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Pop art is exemplified by artists: Andy Warhol, Claes Oldenburg, Wayne Thiebaud, James Rosenquist, Jim Dine, Tom Wesselmann and Roy Lichtenstein among others.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lichtenstein used oil and Magna paint in his best known works, such as *Drowning Girl* (1963), which was appropriated from the lead story in DC Comics' *Secret Hearts* #83.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] (*Drowning Girl* now is in the collection of Museum of Modern Art, New York.) Also featuring thick outlines, bold colors and Ben-Day dots to represent certain colors, as if created by photographic reproduction.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lichtenstein would say of his own work: Abstract Expressionists "put things down on the canvas and responded to what they had done, to the color positions and sizes.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In October 1962 the Sidney Janis Gallery mounted *The New Realists* the first major Pop art group exhibition in an uptown art gallery in New York City.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Sidney Janis mounted the exhibition in a 57th Street storefront near his gallery at 15 E.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The show sent shockwaves through the New York School and reverberated worldwide.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Earlier in the fall of 1962 a historically important and ground-breaking *New Painting of Common Objects* exhibition of Pop art, curated by Walter Hopps at the Pasadena Art Museum sent shock waves across the Western United States.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] *Campbell's Soup Cans* (sometimes referred to as *32 Campbell's Soup Cans*) is the title of an Andy Warhol work of art that was produced in 1962.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It consists of thirty-two canvases, each measuring 20 inches in height x 16 inches in width (50.8 x 40.6 cm) and each consisting of a painting of a Campbell's Soup can—one of each canned soup variety the company offered at the time.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The individual paintings were produced with a semi-mechanised silkscreen process, using a non-painterly style.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] They helped usher in Pop art as a major art movement that relied on themes from popular culture.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These works by Andy Warhol are repetitive and they are made in a non-painterly commercial manner.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Earlier in England in 1956 the term *Pop Art* was used by Lawrence Alloway for paintings that celebrated consumerism of the post World War II era.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This movement rejected Abstract expressionism and its focus on the hermeneutic and psychological interior, in favor of art which depicted, and often celebrated material consumer culture, advertising, and iconography of the mass production age.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The early works of David Hockney whose paintings emerged from England during the 1960s like *A Bigger Splash,* and the works of Richard Hamilton, Peter Blake, and Eduardo Paolozzi, are considered seminal examples in the movement.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] While in the downtown scene in New York's East Village 10th Street galleries artists were formulating an American version of Pop art.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Claes Oldenburg had his storefront, and the Green Gallery on 57th Street began to show Tom Wesselmann and James Rosenquist.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Later Leo Castelli exhibited other American artists including the bulk of the careers of Andy Warhol and Roy Lichtenstein and his use of Benday dots, a technique used in commercial reproduction and seen in ordinary comic books and in paintings like *Drowning Girl*, 1963, in the gallery above.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] There is a connection between the radical works of Duchamp, and Man Ray, the rebellious Dadaists – with a sense of humor; and Pop Artists like Alex Katz (who became known for his parodies of portrait photography and suburban life), Claes Oldenburg, Andy Warhol, Roy Lichtenstein and the others.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1950s and 1960s as abstract painting in America and Europe evolved into movements such as Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, Lyrical Abstraction, and the continuation of Abstract expressionism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] 1),* 1963, Oil on canvas, 60 1/4 x 50 1/2 inches, collection: San Francisco Museum of Modern Art), and later in the 1970s Neo-expressionism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Bay Area Figurative Movement of whom David Park, Elmer Bischoff, Nathan Oliveira and Richard Diebenkorn whose painting *Cityscape 1,* 1963 is a typical example were influential members flourished during the 1950s and 1960s in California.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Younger painters practiced the use of imagery in new and radical ways.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Yves Klein, Martial Raysse, Niki de Saint Phalle, David Hockney, Alex Katz, Antoni Tàpies, Malcolm Morley, Ralph Goings, Audrey Flack, Richard Estes, Chuck Close, Susan Rothenberg, Eric Fischl, John Baeder, and Vija Celmins were a few who became prominent between the 1960s and the 1980s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Fairfield Porter was largely self-taught, and produced representational work in the midst of the Abstract Expressionist movement.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His subjects were primarily landscapes, domestic interiors and portraits of family, friends and fellow artists, many of them affiliated with the New York School of writers, including John Ashbery, Frank O'Hara, and James Schuyler.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Many of his paintings were set in or around the family summer house on Great Spruce Head Island, Maine.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-Dada is a movement that started in the 1950s and 1960s and was related to Abstract expressionism only with imagery.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Featuring the emergence of combined manufactured items, with artist materials, moving away from previous conventions of painting.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This trend in art is exemplified by the work of Jasper Johns and Robert Rauschenberg, whose "combines" in the 1950s were forerunners of Pop Art and Installation art, and made use of the assemblage of large physical objects, including stuffed animals, birds and commercial photography.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1960s and 1970s abstract painting continued to develop in America through varied styles.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Geometric abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Color Field painting and minimal painting, were some interrelated directions for advanced abstract painting as well as some other new movements.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Morris Louis was an important pioneer in advanced Colorfield painting, his work can serve as a bridge between Abstract expressionism, Colorfield painting, and Minimal Art.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Two influential teachers Josef Albers and Hans Hofmann introduced a new generation of American artists to their advanced theories of color and space.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Josef Albers is best remembered for his work as a Geometric abstractionist painter and theorist.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Most famous are the hundreds of paintings and prints that make up the series *Homage to the Square*.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In this rigorous series, begun in 1949, Albers explored chromatic interactions with flat colored squares arranged concentrically on the canvas.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Albers' theories on art and education were formative for the next generation of artists.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His own paintings form the foundation of both hard-edge painting and Op art.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Many Geometric abstract artists, minimalists, and Hard-edge painters elected to use the edges of the image to define the shape of the painting rather than accepting the rectangular format.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In fact, the use of the shaped canvas is primarily associated with paintings of the 1960s and 1970s that are coolly abstract, formalistic, geometrical, objective, rationalistic, clean-lined, brashly sharp-edged, or minimalist in character.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Bykert Gallery, and the Park Place Gallery were important showcases for Minimalism and shaped canvas painting in New York City during the 1960s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In 1965, an exhibition called *The Responsive Eye*, curated by William C.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Seitz, was held at the Museum of Modern Art, in New York City.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The works shown were wide-ranging, encompassing the Minimalism of Frank Stella, the Op art of Larry Poons, the work of Alexander Liberman, alongside the masters of the Op Art movement: Victor Vasarely, Richard Anuszkiewicz, Bridget Riley and others.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The exhibition focused on the perceptual aspects of art, which result both from the illusion of movement and the interaction of color relationships.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art, also known as optical art, is a style present in some paintings and other works of art that use optical illusions.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art is also closely akin to geometric abstraction and hard-edge painting.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Although sometimes the term used for it is perceptual abstraction.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art is a method of painting concerning the interaction between illusion and picture plane, between understanding and seeing.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art works are abstract, with many of the better known pieces made in only black and white.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] When the viewer looks at them, the impression is given of movement, hidden images, flashing and vibration, patterns, or alternatively, of swelling or warping.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting clearly pointed toward a new direction in American painting, away from abstract expressionism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting is related to Post-painterly abstraction, Suprematism, Abstract Expressionism, Hard-edge painting and Lyrical Abstraction.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting sought to rid art of superfluous rhetoric.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Certain artists made references to past or present art, but in general color field painting presents abstraction as an end in itself.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In pursuing this direction of modern art, artists wanted to present each painting as one unified, cohesive, monolithic image.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Frank Stella, Kenneth Noland, Ellsworth Kelly, Barnett Newman, Ronald Davis, Neil Williams, Robert Mangold, Charles Hinman, Richard Tuttle, David Novros, and Alvin Loving are examples of artists associated with the use of the shaped canvas during the period beginning in the early 1960s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] From 1960 Frank Stella produced paintings in aluminium and copper paint and are his first works using shaped canvases (canvases in a shape other than the traditional rectangle or square), often being in L, N, U or T-shapes.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These later developed into more elaborate designs, in the *Irregular Polygon* series (67), for example.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Also in the 1960s, Stella began to use a wider range of colors, typically arranged in straight or curved lines.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Later he began his *Protractor Series* (71) of paintings, in which arcs, sometimes overlapping, within square borders are arranged side-by-side to produce full and half circles painted in rings of concentric color.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] *Harran II,* 1967, is an example of the *Protractor Series*.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These paintings are named after circular cities he had visited while in the Middle East earlier in the 1960s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Irregular Polygon canvases and Protractor series further extended the concept of the shaped canvas.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Andre Emmerich Gallery, the Leo Castelli Gallery, the Richard Feigen Gallery, and the Park Place Gallery were important showcases for Color Field painting, shaped canvas painting and Lyrical Abstraction in New York City during the 1960s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1960s Color Field painting and Minimal art were often closely associated with each other.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In actuality by the early 1970s both movements became decidedly diverse.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Another related movement of the late 1960s, Lyrical Abstraction (the term being coined by Larry Aldrich, the founder of the Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum, Ridgefield Connecticut), encompassed what Aldrich said he saw in the studios of many artists at that time.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It is also the name of an exhibition that originated in the Aldrich Museum and traveled to the Whitney Museum of American Art and other museums throughout the United States between 1969 and 1971.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Postminimalism often incorporating industrial materials, raw materials, fabrications, found objects, installation, serial repetition, and often with references to Dada and Surrealism is best exemplified in the sculptures of Eva Hesse.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lyrical Abstraction is a type of freewheeling abstract painting that emerged in the mid-1960s when abstract painters returned to various forms of painterly, pictorial, expressionism with a predominate focus on process, gestalt and repetitive compositional strategies in general.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lyrical Abstraction shares similarities with Color Field painting and Abstract Expressionism especially in the freewheeling usage of paint – texture and surface.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Direct drawing, calligraphic use of line, the effects of brushed, splattered, stained, squeegeed, poured, and splashed paint superficially resemble the effects seen in Abstract Expressionism and Color Field painting.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] However the styles are markedly different.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Setting it apart from Abstract Expressionism and Action Painting of the 1940s and 1950s is the approach to composition and drama.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] As seen in Action Painting there is an emphasis on brushstrokes, high compositional drama, dynamic compositional tension.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] While in Lyrical Abstraction as exemplified by the 1971 Ronnie Landfield painting *Garden of Delight* (above), there is a sense of compositional randomness, all over composition, low key and relaxed compositional drama and an emphasis on process, repetition, and an all over sensibility.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Donald Judd had started as a painter, and ended as a creator of objects.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His seminal essay, "Specific Objects" (published in Arts Yearbook 8, 1965), was a touchstone of theory for the formation of Minimalist aesthetics.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In this essay, Judd found a starting point for a new territory for American art, and a simultaneous rejection of residual inherited European artistic values.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] He pointed to evidence of this development in the works of an array of artists active in New York at the time, including Jasper Johns, Dan Flavin and Lee Bontecou.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Of "preliminary" importance for Judd was the work of George Earl Ortman, who had concretized and distilled painting's forms into blunt, tough, philosophically charged geometries.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These Specific Objects inhabited a space not then comfortably classifiable as either painting or sculpture.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] That the categorical identity of such objects was itself in question, and that they avoided easy association with well-worn and over-familiar conventions, was a part of their value for Judd.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] American painters such as Brice Marden and Cy Twombly show a clear European influence in their *pure* abstraction, minimalist painting of the 1960s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Ronald Davis polyurethane works from the late 1960s pay homage to the *Broken Glass* of Marcel Duchamp.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This movement was heavily criticised by high modernist formalist art critics and historians.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Some anxious critics thought Minimalist art represented a misunderstanding of the modern dialectic of painting and sculpture as defined by critic Clement Greenberg, arguably the dominant American critic of painting in the period leading up to the 1960s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The most notable critique of Minimalism was produced by Michael Fried, a Greenbergian critic, who objected to the work on the basis of its "theatricality".
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In *Art and Objecthood* (published in Artforum in June 1967) he declared that the Minimalist work of art, particularly Minimalist sculpture, was based on an engagement with the physicality of the spectator.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] He argued that work like Robert Morris's transformed the act of viewing into a type of spectacle, in which the artifice of the act observation and the viewer's participation in the work were unveiled.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Fried saw this displacement of the viewer's experience from an aesthetic engagement within, to an event outside of the artwork as a failure of Minimal art.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Ad Reinhardt, actually an artist of the Abstract Expressionist generation, but one whose reductive all-black paintings seemed to anticipate minimalism, had this to say about the value of a reductive approach to art: "The more stuff in it, the busier the work of art, the worse it is.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Still other important innovations in abstract painting took place during the 1960s and the 1970s characterized by monochrome painting and hard-edge painting inspired by Ad Reinhardt, Barnett Newman, Milton Resnick, and Ellsworth Kelly.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Artists as diverse as Agnes Martin, Al Held, Larry Zox, Frank Stella, Larry Poons, Brice Marden and others explored the power of simplification.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The convergence of Color Field painting, minimal art, hard-edge painting, Lyrical Abstraction, and postminimalism blurred the distinction between movements that became more apparent in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The neo-expressionism movement is related to earlier developments in abstract expressionism, neo-Dada, Lyrical Abstraction and postminimal painting.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These works were inspirational to a new generation of painters interested in a revival of expressive imagery.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His painting *Painting, Smoking, Eating* 1973, seen above in the gallery is an example of Guston's final and conclusive return to representation.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In the late 1970s and early 1980s, there was also a return to painting that occurred almost simultaneously in Italy, Germany, France and Britain.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These movements were called Transavantguardia, Neue Wilde, Figuration Libre, Neo-expressionism, the school of London, and in the late 1990s the Stuckists, a group that emerged late in 1990s respectively.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These painting were characterized by large formats, free expressive mark making, figuration, myth and imagination.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] All work in this genre came to be labeled neo-expressionism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Some critics regarded it as driven by profit motivations by large commercial galleries.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This type of art continues in popularity into the 21st century, even after the art crash of the late 1980s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the late 1970s in the United States painters who began working with invigorated surfaces and who returned to imagery like Susan Rothenberg gained in popularity, especially as seen above in paintings like *Horse 2,* 1979.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1980s American artists like Eric Fischl, David Salle, Jean-Michel Basquiat (who began as a graffiti artist), Julian Schnabel, and Keith Haring, and Italian painters like Mimmo Paladino, Sandro Chia, and Enzo Cucchi, among others defined the idea of Neo-expressionism in America.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-expressionism was a style of modern painting that became popular in the late 1970s and dominated the art market until the mid-1980s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It developed in Europe as a reaction against the conceptual and minimalistic art of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-expressionists returned to portraying recognizable objects, such as the human body (although sometimes in a virtually abstract manner), in a rough and violently emotional way using vivid colours and banal colour harmonies.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The veteran painters Philip Guston, Frank Auerbach, Leon Kossoff, Gerhard Richter, A.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Penck and Georg Baselitz, along with slightly younger artists like Anselm Kiefer, Eric Fischl, Susan Rothenberg, Francesco Clemente, Damien Hirst, Jean-Michel Basquiat, Julian Schnabel, Keith Haring, and many others became known for working in this intense expressionist vein of painting.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] At the beginning of the 21st century Contemporary painting and Contemporary art in general continues in several contiguous modes, characterized by the idea of pluralism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Mainstream painting has been rejected by artists of the postmodern era in favor of artistic pluralism.
[src:ancient-greece/20th-century-western-painting-p02] According to art critic Arthur Danto there is an *anything goes* attitude that prevails; an "everything going on", and consequently "nothing going on" syndrome; this creates an aesthetic traffic jam with no firm and clear direction and with every lane on the artistic superhighway filled to capacity.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas himself and some contemporary historians have described the government as totalitarian.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] In its symbolism and rhetoric, the regime took inspiration from Fascist Italy, but it retained close links to Britain and the French Third Republic, rather than the Axis powers.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Being non-partisan, after Metaxas' death in January 1941, the regime hinged entirely on the King.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas imposed his regime primarily to fight the turbulent social situation prevalent in Greece in the 1930s, in which political factionalization had disrupted Greek parliamentary democracy.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The sinking credibility of the Parliament was accompanied by several coup attempts; a Venizelist putsch failed in March 1935, and in the following October, elections reinforced the Royalist majority, which allowed the exiled King George II to return to Greece.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The king re-established the monarchy in the country, but the parliament, split into incompatible factions, was unable to shape a clear political majority and form a government.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Meanwhile, the increasing activity of the Communists, whose 15 deputies from the 1936 elections held the balance between 143 Monarchists and 142 Liberals, Agrarians, and Republicans, created a deadlock.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] In May 1936, widespread agrarian unrest among tobacco farmers and industrial unrest in the north of the country erupted, which eventually brought General Metaxas to suspend the parliament on the eve of a major strike, on 4 August 1936.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Endorsed by the King, Metaxas declared a state of emergency, decreed martial law, annulled various articles of the constitution, and established a crisis cabinet to put an end to the unrest and to restore the social order.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Thus the Metaxas dictatorship was born, and the period of time which would follow was named after the day Metaxas rose to absolute power: 4 August.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The new regime was backed by small extremist political parties, and by conservatives expecting a crackdown on the communists.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The roots of Metaxas' "New State" were sought in Greece's classical history.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas thought Greek nationalism would galvanize "the heathen values of ancient Greece, specifically those of Sparta, along with the Eastern Orthodox Christian values of the Medieval empire of Byzantium".
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Ancient Macedonia was also glorified as the first political unifier of the Hellenes.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] As its main symbol, the youth organization of the regime chose the labrys/pelekys, the symbol of ancient Minoan Crete.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The traditional Greek values of "Country, Loyalty, Family and Religion", which Metaxas praised repeatedly, were also close to those of the ancient Spartans.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The regime promoted the perceived Spartan ideals of self-discipline, militarism and collective sacrifice, while Byzantium provided an emphasis on a centralized state and devotion to the monarchy and Greek Orthodox Church.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas considered António Salazar's Estado Novo of Portugal his main inspiration and surrounded himself with elements from this and other dictatorial regimes of the time.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas' regime also developed characteristics typical of authoritarian states such as 1930s Italy and Germany: the regime's propaganda presented Metaxas as "the First Peasant", "the First Worker" and as "the National Father" of the Greeks.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The Metaxas regime sought to comprehensively change Greece, and therefore instituted controls on Greek society, politics, language, and the economy.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] In each of these policy areas, the Metaxas government seemed more nearly an anticipation of Francoist Spain than to resemble its contemporaries Nazi Germany or Fascist Italy.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Having come to power intent on restoring public order, Metaxas' state largely achieved this goal, under the supervision of what can be described as its most fascist member, minister of public order Konstantinos Maniadakis.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Maniadakis created a second fake "communist party", published a fake *Rizospastis* and achieved the dissolution of all the communist organizations.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas' policies such as the censorship of the media, the banning of political parties and prohibition of strikes copied contemporary European authoritarian regimes.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] As its far-right contemporaries Italy and Germany, the Greek State also had its political police force, the *Asfaleia*, based upon the Gestapo (its chief Maniadakis maintained a close relationship with Himmler on methods and techniques).
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The objective of Asfaleia was to secure public order.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The regime also repressed the rebetiko music due to the uncompromising lyrics and favoured the traditional Greek folk music.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Hashish dens, baglamas and bouzouki were banned, or at least playing in the eastern-style manner and scales.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Probably inspired by the *Völkisch movement*, a massive promotion of the Greek folk music took place, though the radio and public festivals, mainly because of the animosity of the state towards the bouzoukis and the rebetiko music.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] On this point the Greek communist left agreed, considering the rebetiko as "reactionary".
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Soon after its inception the regime severely repressed the communists and leftists.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] About 15,000 people were arrested and jailed, or exiled for political reasons; some were subjected to torture.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas' regime forced the Communist party underground, and also attempted to dismantle the old system of loyalties of the Royalist and Venizelist parties.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Those major forces however remained, as they had for the preceding decades, and re-emerged immediately after the four-year Metaxas regime.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] While Metaxas' regime did play up the communist threat in order to justify its repression, the regime is not known to have committed political murders and did not instate the death penalty.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Dissidents were, rather, usually banished to tiny islands in the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] For example, the liberal leader George Papandreou was exiled to Andros.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The Greek Communist Party (KKE), meanwhile, which had already been outlawed, remained intact.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Legal restrictions against it finally were ended in 1974 during metapolitefsi.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas was educated in the German Empire and admired German culture.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] He supported the arts (theatrical, literary, musical, visual arts, etc.).
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] He collaborated with significant intellectual figures of the era, like Stratis Myrivilis, Nikos Kazantzakis, Angelos Sikelianos, Manolis Kalomoiris, Angelos Terzakis, "Nelly's" (Elli Seraidari), and others, to promote the ideas of the regime, especially to the youth.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Another notable policy was the use and promotion of Demotic Greek (*Demotiki*) in the educational system (but in a conservative form), instead of *Katharevousa*.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Manolis Triantafyllidis was appointed to create the Demotic grammar used.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] In order to keep and maintain the values of the regime in future years, Metaxas gave birth to the *Ethniki Organosi Neolaias* (Εθνική Οργάνωση Νεολαίας, National Organisation of Youth, EON).
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The EON brought together youths of all economic and social strata into one single body.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Boys' education emphasized discipline and physical training, while girls were taught to become supportive wives and caring mothers to breed a stronger, healthier new generation.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The EON published a fortnightly magazine called *Neolaia* (Νεολαία, Greek for "Youth"), which had much influence both in schools and in higher education.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas' vision was to create, through the youth, the "Third Hellenic Civilization", a continuity of the ancient Greek and Byzantine civilization.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The EON was disbanded by the German-Italian occupying authority in Greece following its vigorous resistance of the invasion.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] As with many nation states at the time, he used language exalting his people's race.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Ethnic and linguistic minorities (mainly Slavic-speakers of Greek Macedonia) were persecuted under Metaxas' rule.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The regime, however, was tolerant to the Greek Jews, repealing the anti-Semitic laws of previous regimes.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] A large community of Sephardic Jews was present in the region of Thessaloniki which was annexed by Greece in 1913, and Jews were largely in opposition to Venizelism.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas was firmly opposed to the irredentist factions of the Slavophones of northern Greece (most of whom were Bulgarians), some of whom underwent political persecution due to advocacy of irredentism with regard to neighbouring countries.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas' regime continued repression of the use of Slavic languages both in public and in private and of expressions of Slavic cultural distinctiveness.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] During World War II, the Greek-identifying Slavophones fought in the Hellenic Army in defense of Greece, whereas those who didn't, collaborated with the occupational forces following Greece's capitulation.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Again, in contrast to some totalitarian regimes, no mass killings were ever instituted and there is no evidence that any were planned.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] One of 4 August government's main objectives was the repudiation of the old capitalist system and its replacement with a corporatist economic system in order to promote national and social solidarity.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] This idea "harmonized perfectly with Metaxas' convictions on social and national solidarity as well as his rejection of individualism and class struggle".
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The plan for the creation of a corporatist state was manifest in the early days of the regime by public declarations by Metaxas and by government ministers.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] To this end, Deputy Premier and Finance Minister Konstantinos Zavitsianos "published details about a horizontal (according to branches of production), not vertical (according to social class), syndicalist organization" of the state.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] However, due to the external crisis with Italy, the plan had to be temporarily postponed with the result that it never fully materialized.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Many elements of this program persist in Greek economic policy.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas' regime founded the Workers' Center (Εργατικό Κέντρο), which was established to look after workers' housing and recreation, among other things.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The 4th of August regime initially stabilized the drachma, which had been suffering from high inflation.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Exploiting the newfound solidity of the currency, Metaxas' government embarked on large public works programs (such as the Ellinikon International Airport), including land drainage, construction of railways, road improvements, and modernization of the telecommunications infrastructure.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas' economic program met with initial success, with a marked rise in per capita income and temporary decline in unemployment in Greece between 1936 and 1938 (unemployment skyrocketed after 1938).
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Capitalizing on this success, the government instituted debt relief for farmers and instituted price floors on some agricultural goods to redistribute wealth to the countryside.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Also, on the legislation sector the Greek civil code, was finally completed by a jurist commission; a plan pending since the years of Otto of Greece.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Another organization established by the regime was for the first time a state radio station; the YRE (today ERT), suitable also for the propaganda of the regime.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Also, during the years of the regime, the first law was made to establish the National parks of Greece, as an example of the physiolatry, promoted by the regime.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] However, during these years, Ilissos river was covered in Athens.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] There is some debate over the regime's relationship to other far-right regimes of the 1930s, especially Fascist Italy and Nazi Germany.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Foreign policy was one of the main concerns of 4 August regime.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas, who had studied in Germany as a youth, was pro-German, while the King was pro-British.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] This caused heated discussions between the two, but the reality of 1930s Europe was that Greece's security depended less on Germany than on her traditional ally and protector, the United Kingdom, which was the Great Power dominating the Eastern Mediterranean Sea with her fleet.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] In addition, Italian leader Benito Mussolini's grandiose schemes to build a new Roman Empire in the Mediterranean directly clashed with Greek pretensions to control the Aegean Sea and the Dodecanese islands (then under Italian control) and to exert stronger influence in Albania.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] As tensions and threat of war increased in Europe just before World War II, the situation was almost exactly the same as the position before World War I, when Greece had strong pro-German affinities in government, but it depended on Great Britain for its security.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Most observers were anticipating Greece would attempt to remain neutral.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas indeed attempted to maintain strict neutrality, but Italian expansionism eventually led to an Italian ultimatum and to the Greco-Italian War.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] However, Greek forces repelled the Italian invasion completely and pushed the Italians back into Albania, where the invasion had been launched.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] In fact, some territories in Albania where the Greek minority lives were claimed to be '*alliberated*' and Metaxas' plans were to unite them with the rest of Greece.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas died suddenly in January 1941 in uncertain circumstances.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] His death raised hopes of a liberalization of his regime and the restoration of parliamentary rule, but King George quashed these hopes when he retained the regime's machinery in place.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] In the meantime, Germany entered the Battle of Greece through Yugoslavia and Bulgaria on April 6, 1941.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Metaxas' successor Prime Minister Alexandros Koryzis, committed suicide on April 18, 1941, when the Germans approached Athens.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] On April 27, 1941, Athens was occupied by the Germans.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Despite British assistance, by the end of May, the Germans had overrun most of the country.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The 4th of August regime collapsed on May 29, 1941.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The King and the government escaped to Crete, where they stayed until the end of the Battle of Crete.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] They then transferred to Egypt, where a Greek government in exile was established.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] An alternative destination of Cyprus was rejected by the British, who feared that it might reinforce Greek claims on the island.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] Meanwhile, in Greece a fascist puppet government was placed into power by the Axis powers.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] As the Axis occupation ended, Greece descended into civil war between the communist-dominated forces of the left, operating in Greece and from bases in the south of Yugoslavia, and the U.S.- and UK-aligned forces of the political right.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] This was the first major protracted combat of the Cold War, one of the first exercises in U.S. policy of Containment, and a subject of the Truman Doctrine of U.S.
[src:ancient-greece/4th-of-august-regime] The alignments were quite different from the Venizelist-Monarchist National Schism, as most Venizelists supported the right-wing alliance during the civil war.
[src:ancient-greece/abcanz-armies] The program started in 1947 as the "Plan to Effect Standardization" between the armies of the United States, United Kingdom, and Canada (the ABC Armies), with the three nations looking to capitalize on the close cooperation between the forces during World War II.
[src:ancient-greece/abcanz-armies] In 1954, the Plan was replaced by the "Basic Standardization Concept".
[src:ancient-greece/abcanz-armies] Australia joined the organization in 1963, and the ABCA Program was established with the ratification of the "Basic Standardization Agreement 1964" on 1 October 1964.
[src:ancient-greece/abcanz-armies] In 1965, Australia successfully sponsored the introduction of New Zealand to the agreement as an observer.
[src:ancient-greece/abcanz-armies] Originally, the role of ABCANZ was limited to issues of standardization for soldier equipment, training, and tactics.
[src:ancient-greece/abcanz-armies] Following the September 11 attacks, a review by the Program's Heads of Delegations saw the Program modified to address the changing security environment and improve responsiveness, relevance, and focus on interoperability.
[src:ancient-greece/abcanz-armies] The overhaul was completed by June 2004.
[src:ancient-greece/abcanz-armies] Also in 2004, the increasing involvement of the United States Marine Corps was formally recognized with a Memorandum of Understanding between the Corps and the United States Army, allowing both forces to be represented by a single position.
[src:ancient-greece/abcanz-armies] Following this, the United Kingdom delegation successfully incorporated the Royal Marines.
[src:ancient-greece/abcanz-armies] New Zealand became a full member of ABCA in early 2006.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Three centuries after the decline of Mycenaean Greece during the Bronze Age collapse, Greek urban poleis began to form in the 8th century BC, ushering in the Archaic period and the colonization of the Mediterranean Basin.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] This was followed by the age of Classical Greece, from the Greco-Persian Wars to the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC, and which included the Golden Age of Athens and the Peloponnesian War between Athens and Sparta.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The unification of Greece by Macedon under Philip II and subsequent conquest of the Achaemenid Empire by Alexander the Great spread Hellenistic civilization across the Middle East.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period is considered to have ended in 30 BC, when the last Hellenistic kingdom, Ptolemaic Egypt, was annexed by the Roman Republic.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Classical Greek culture, especially philosophy, had a powerful influence on ancient Rome, which carried a version of it throughout the Mediterranean and much of Europe.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] For this reason, Classical Greece is generally considered the cradle of Western civilization, the seminal culture from which the modern West derives many of its founding archetypes and ideas in politics, philosophy, science, and art.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in the Mediterranean region is commonly considered to have begun in the 8th century BC (around the time of the earliest recorded poetry of Homer) and ended in the 6th century AD.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in Greece was preceded by the Greek Dark Ages (c.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] 800 BC), archaeologically characterised by the protogeometric and geometric styles of designs on pottery.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Following the Dark Ages was the Archaic period, beginning around the 8th century BC, which saw early developments in Greek culture and society leading to the Classical period from the Persian invasion of Greece in 480 BC until the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Classical period is characterized by a "classical" style, i.e. one which was considered exemplary by later observers, most famously in the Parthenon of Athens.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Politically, the Classical period was dominated by Athens and the Delian League during the 5th century, but displaced by Spartan hegemony during the early 4th century BC, before power shifted to Thebes and the Boeotian League and finally to the League of Corinth led by Macedon.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] This period was shaped by the Greco-Persian Wars, the Peloponnesian War, and the Rise of Macedon.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Following the Classical period was the Hellenistic period (323–146 BC), during which Greek culture and power expanded into the Near East from the death of Alexander until the Roman conquest.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Roman Greece is usually counted from the Roman victory over the Corinthians at the Battle of Corinth in 146 BC to the establishment of Byzantium by Constantine as the capital of the Roman Empire in 330 AD.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Finally, Late Antiquity refers to the period of Christianization during the later 4th to early 6th centuries AD, consummated by the closure of the Academy of Athens by Justinian I in 529.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The historical period of ancient Greece is unique in world history as the first period attested directly in comprehensive, narrative historiography, while earlier ancient history or protohistory is known from much more fragmentary documents such as annals, king lists, and pragmatic epigraphy.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Herodotus is widely known as the "father of history": his *Histories* are eponymous of the entire field.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Written between the 450s and 420s BC, Herodotus' work reaches about a century into the past, discussing 6th-century BC historical figures such as Darius I of Persia, Cambyses II and Psamtik III, and alluding to some 8th-century BC persons such as Candaules.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The accuracy of Herodotus' works is debated.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Herodotus was succeeded by authors such as Thucydides, Xenophon, Demosthenes, Plato and Aristotle.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Most were either Athenian or pro-Athenian, which is why far more is known about the history and politics of Athens than of many other cities.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Their scope is further limited by a focus on political, military and diplomatic history, ignoring economic and social history.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The archaic period, lasting approximately from 800 to 500 BC, saw the culmination of political and social developments which had begun in the Greek Dark Age, with the *polis* (city-state) becoming the most important unit of political organisation in Greece.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The absence of powerful states in Greece after the collapse of Mycenaean power, and the geography of Greece, where many settlements were separated from their neighbours by mountainous terrain, encouraged the development of small independent city-states.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Several Greek states saw tyrants rise to power in this period, most famously at Corinth from 657 BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The period also saw the founding of Greek colonies around the Mediterranean, with Euboean settlements at Al-Mina in the east as early as 800 BC, and Ischia in the west by 775.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Increasing contact with non-Greek peoples in this period, especially in the Near East, inspired developments in art and architecture, the adoption of coinage, and the development of the Greek alphabet.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Athens developed its democratic system over the course of the archaic period.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Already in the 7th century, the right of all citizen men to attend the assembly appears to have been established.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] After a failed coup led by Cylon of Athens around 636 BC, Draco was appointed to establish a code of laws in 621.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] This failed to reduce the political tension between the poor and the elites, and in 594 Solon was given the authority to enact another set of reforms, which attempted to balance the power of the rich and the poor.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the middle of the 6th century, Pisistratus established himself as a tyrant, and after his death in 527 his son Hippias inherited his position; by the end of the 6th century he had been overthrown, and Cleisthenes carried out further democratising reforms.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In Sparta, a political system with two kings, a council of elders, and five ephors developed over the course of the 8th and 7th centuries.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] According to Spartan tradition, this constitution was established by the legendary lawgiver Lycurgus.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Over the course of the First Messenian War and Second Messenian War, Sparta subjugated the neighbouring region of Messenia, enserfing the population.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the 6th century, Greek city-states began to develop formal relationships with one another, where previously individual rulers had relied on personal relationships with the elites of other cities.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Towards the end of the Archaic period, Sparta began to build a series of alliances, the Peloponnesian League, with cities including Corinth, Elis, and Megara, isolating Messenia and reinforcing Sparta's position against Argos, the other major power in the Peloponnese.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Other alliances in the 6th century included those between Elis and Heraea in the Peloponnese; and between the Greek colony Sybaris in southern Italy, its allies, and the Serdaioi.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In 499 BC, the Ionian city-states under Persian rule rebelled against their Persian-supported tyrant rulers.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Supported by troops sent from Athens and Eretria, they advanced as far as Sardis and burnt the city before being driven back by a Persian counterattack.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The revolt continued until 494, when the rebelling Ionians were defeated.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Darius did not forget that Athens had assisted the Ionian revolt, and in 490 he assembled an armada to retaliate.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Though heavily outnumbered, the Athenians—supported by their Plataean allies—defeated the Persian hordes at the Battle of Marathon, and the Persian fleet turned tail.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Ten years later, a second invasion was launched by Darius' son Xerxes.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The city-states of northern and central Greece submitted to the Persian forces without resistance, but a coalition of 31 Greek city-states, including Athens and Sparta, determined to resist the Persian invaders.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] At the same time, Greek Sicily was invaded by a Carthaginian force.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Persians were decisively defeated at sea by a primarily Athenian naval force at the Battle of Salamis, and on land in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The alliance against Persia continued, initially led by the Spartan Pausanias but from 477 by Athens, and by 460 Persia had been driven out of the Aegean.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] During this long campaign, the Delian League gradually transformed from a defensive alliance of Greek states into an Athenian empire, as Athens' growing naval power intimidated the other league states.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Athens ended its campaigns against Persia in 450, after a disastrous defeat in Egypt in 454, and the death of Cimon in action against the Persians on Cyprus in 450.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] As the Athenian fight against the Persian empire waned, conflict grew between Athens and Sparta.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Suspicious of the increasing Athenian power funded by the Delian League, Sparta offered aid to reluctant members of the League to rebel against Athenian domination.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] These tensions were exacerbated in 462 BC when Athens sent a force to aid Sparta in overcoming a helot revolt, but this aid was rejected by the Spartans.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the 450s, Athens took control of Boeotia, and won victories over Aegina and Corinth.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] However, Athens failed to win a decisive victory, and in 447 lost Boeotia again.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Athens and Sparta signed the Thirty Years' Peace in the winter of 446/445, ending the conflict.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Despite the treaty, Athenian relations with Sparta declined again in the 430s, and in 431 BC the Peloponnesian War began.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The first phase of the war saw a series of fruitless annual invasions of Attica by Sparta, while Athens successfully fought the Corinthian empire in northwest Greece and defended its own empire, despite a plague which killed the leading Athenian statesman Pericles.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The war turned after Athenian victories led by Cleon at Pylos and Sphakteria, and Sparta sued for peace, but the Athenians rejected the proposal.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Athenian failure to regain control of Boeotia at Delium and Brasidas' successes in northern Greece in 424 improved Sparta's position after Sphakteria.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] After the deaths of Cleon and Brasidas, the strongest proponents of war on each side, a peace treaty was negotiated in 421 by the Athenian general Nicias.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In 418 BC allied forces of Athens and Argos were defeated by Sparta at Mantinea.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In 415 Athens launched an ambitious naval expedition to dominate Sicily; the expedition ended in disaster at the harbor of Syracuse, with almost the entire army killed, and the ships destroyed.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Soon after the Athenian defeat in Syracuse, Athens' Ionian allies began to rebel against the Delian league, while Persia began to once again involve itself in Greek affairs on the Spartan side.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Initially the Athenian position continued relatively strong, with important victories at Cyzicus in 410 and Arginusae in 406.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] However, in 405 the Spartan Lysander defeated Athens in the Battle of Aegospotami, and began to blockade Athens' harbour; driven by hunger, Athens sued for peace, agreeing to surrender their fleet and join the Spartan-led Peloponnesian League.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Following the Athenian surrender, Sparta installed an oligarchic regime, the Thirty Tyrants, in Athens, one of a number of Spartan-backed oligarchies which rose to power after the Peloponnesian war.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Spartan predominance did not last: after only a year, the Thirty had been overthrown.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The first half of the 4th century saw the major Greek states attempt to dominate the mainland; none were successful, and their resulting weakness led to a power vacuum which was eventually filled by Macedon under Philip II and then Alexander the Great.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the immediate aftermath of the Peloponnesian war, Sparta attempted to extend their own power, leading Argos, Athens, Corinth, and Thebes to join against them.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Aiming to prevent any single Greek state gaining the dominance that would allow it to challenge Persia, the Persian king initially joined the alliance against Sparta, before imposing the Peace of Antalcidas ("King's Peace") which restored Persia's control over the Anatolian Greeks.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] By 371 BC, Thebes was in the ascendancy, defeating Sparta at the Battle of Leuctra, killing the Spartan king Cleombrotus I, and invading Laconia.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Further Theban successes against Sparta in 369 led to Messenia gaining independence; Sparta never recovered from the loss of Messenia's fertile land and the helot workforce it provided.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The rising power of Thebes led Sparta and Athens to join forces; in 362 they were defeated by Thebes at the Battle of Mantinea.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the aftermath of Mantinea, none of the major Greek states were able to dominate.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Though Thebes had won the battle, their general Epaminondas was killed, and they spent the following decades embroiled in wars with their neighbours; Athens, meanwhile, saw its second naval alliance, formed in 377, collapse in the mid-350s.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The power vacuum in Greece after the Battle of Mantinea was filled by Macedon, under Philip II, starting from the battle of Crocus field.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In 338 BC, he defeated a Greek alliance at the Battle of Chaeronea, and subsequently formed the League of Corinth.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Philip planned to lead the League to invade Persia, but was murdered in 336 BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] His son Alexander the Great was left to fulfill his father's ambitions.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] After campaigns against Macedon's western and northern enemies, and those Greek states that had broken from the League of Corinth following the death of Philip, Alexander began his campaign against Persia in 334 BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] He conquered Persia, defeating Darius III at the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, and after the Battle of Gaugamela in 331 BC proclaimed himself king of Asia.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] From 329 BC he led expeditions to Bactria and then India; further plans to invade Arabia and North Africa were halted by his death in 323 BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The period from the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC until the death of Cleopatra, the last Macedonian ruler of Egypt, is known as the Hellenistic period.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the early part of this period, a new form of kingship developed based on Macedonian and Near Eastern traditions.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The first Hellenistic kings were previously Alexander's generals, and took power in the period following his death, though they were not part of existing royal lineages and lacked historic claims to the territories they controlled.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the early part of the Hellenistic period, the exact borders of the Hellenistic kingdoms were not settled.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Antigonus attempted to expand his territory by attacking the other successor kingdoms until they joined against him, and he was killed at the Battle of Ipsus in 301 BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] His son Demetrius spent many years in Seleucid captivity, and his son, Antigonus II, only reclaimed the Macedonian throne around 276.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Meanwhile, the Seleucid kingdom gave up territory in the east to the Indian king Chandragupta Maurya in exchange for war elephants, and later lost large parts of Persia to the Parthian Empire.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] By the mid-3rd century, the kingdoms of Alexander's successors was mostly stable, though there continued to be disputes over border areas.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The great capitals of Hellenistic culture were Alexandria in the Ptolemaic Kingdom and Antioch in the Seleucid Empire.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The conquests of Alexander had numerous consequences for the Greek city-states.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] It greatly widened the horizons of the Greeks and led to a steady emigration of the young and ambitious to the new Greek empires in the east.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Many Greeks migrated to Alexandria, Antioch and the many other new Hellenistic cities founded in Alexander's wake, as far away as present-day Afghanistan and Pakistan, where the Greco-Bactrian Kingdom and the Indo-Greek Kingdom survived until the end of the 1st century BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Some city-states within Greece formed themselves into two major leagues; the Achaean League (including Corinth and Argos) and the Aetolian League.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] For much of the period until the Roman conquest, these leagues were at war, often participating in the conflicts between the Diadochi's successor states to Alexander's empire.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Antigonid Kingdom became involved in a war with the Roman Republic in the late 3rd century.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Although the First Macedonian War was inconclusive, the Romans, in typical fashion, continued to fight Macedon until it was completely absorbed into the Roman Republic (by 149 BC).
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the east, the unwieldy Seleucid Empire gradually disintegrated, although a rump survived until 64 BC, whilst the Ptolemaic Kingdom continued in Egypt until 30 BC when it too was conquered by the Romans.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Aetolian league grew wary of Roman involvement in Greece, and sided with the Seleucids in the Roman–Seleucid War; when the Romans were victorious, the league was effectively absorbed into the Republic.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Although the Achaean league outlasted both the Aetolian league and Macedon, it was also soon defeated and absorbed by the Romans in 146 BC, bringing Greek independence to an end.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Greek peninsula came under Roman rule during the 146 BC conquest of Greece after the Battle of Corinth.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Macedonia became a Roman province while southern Greece came under the surveillance of Macedonia's prefect; however, some Greek *poleis* managed to maintain a partial independence and avoid taxation.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Aegean Islands were added to this territory in 133 BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Athens and other Greek cities revolted in 88 BC, and the peninsula was crushed by the Roman general Sulla.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Roman civil wars devastated the land even further, until Augustus organized the peninsula as the province of Achaea in 27 BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Greece was a key eastern province of the Roman Empire, as the Roman culture had long been in fact Greco-Roman.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Greek language served as a *lingua franca* in the East and in Italy, and many Greek intellectuals such as Galen would perform most of their work in Rome.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The territory of Greece is mountainous, and as a result, ancient Greece consisted of many smaller regions, each with its own dialect, cultural peculiarities, and identity.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Regionalism and regional conflicts were prominent features of ancient Greece.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Cities tended to be located in valleys between mountains, or on coastal plains, and dominated a certain area around them.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the south lay the Peloponnese, consisting of the regions of Laconia (southeast), Messenia (southwest), Elis (west), Achaia (north), Korinthia (northeast), Argolis (east), and Arcadia (center).
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] These names survive to the present day as regional units of modern Greece, though with somewhat different boundaries.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Mainland Greece to the north, nowadays known as Central Greece, consisted of Aetolia and Acarnania in the west, Locris, Doris, and Phocis in the center, while in the east lay Boeotia, Attica, and Megaris.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Northeast lay Thessaly, while Epirus lay to the northwest.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Epirus stretched from the Ambracian Gulf in the south to the Ceraunian Mountains and the Aoos river in the north, and consisted of Chaonia (north), Molossia (center), and Thesprotia (south).
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the northeast corner was Macedonia, originally consisting Lower Macedonia and its regions, such as Emathia (Macedonia), Pieria, and Bottiaea, and later Almopia, Amphaxitis.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The original capital of Macedon was Aigai and then moved to Pella in the 4th century BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] To the north of Macedonia lay various non-Greek peoples such as the Paeonians due north, the Thracians to the northeast, and the Illyrians, with whom the Macedonians were frequently in conflict, to the northwest.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Chalcidice was settled early on by southern Greek colonists and was considered part of the Greek world, while from the late 2nd millennium BC substantial Greek settlement also occurred on the eastern shores of the Aegean, in Anatolia.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] This was not simply for trade, but also to found settlements.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] These Greek colonies were not, as Roman colonies were, dependent on their mother-city, but were independent city-states in their own right.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Greeks settled outside of Greece in two distinct ways.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The first was in permanent settlements founded by Greeks, which formed as independent poleis.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The second form was in what historians refer to as *emporia*; trading posts which were occupied by both Greeks and non-Greeks and which were primarily concerned with the manufacture and sale of goods.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Examples of this latter type of settlement are found at Al Mina in the east and Pithekoussai in the west.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] From around 750 to 500 BC, Greeks settled colonies in all directions.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] To the east, the Aegean coast of Asia Minor was colonized first, followed by Cyprus and the coasts of Thrace, the Sea of Marmara and the south coast of the Black Sea.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Eventually, Greek colonization reached as far northeast as present-day Ukraine and Russia (Taganrog).
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] To the west the coasts of Illyria, Southern Italy (called "Magna Graecia") were settled, followed by Southern France, Corsica, and even eastern Spain.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Greek colonies were also founded in Egypt and Libya.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Modern Syracuse, Naples, Marseille and Istanbul had their beginnings as the Greek colonies Syracusae (Συράκουσαι), Neapolis (Νεάπολις), Massalia (Μασσαλία) and Byzantion (Βυζάντιον).
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] These colonies played an important role in the spread of Greek influence throughout Europe and also aided in the establishment of long-distance trading networks between the Greek city-states, boosting the economy of ancient Greece.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Ancient Greece consisted of several hundred relatively independent city-states (*poleis*).
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] This was a situation unlike that in most other contemporary societies, which were either tribal or kingdoms ruling over relatively large territories.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Undoubtedly, the geography of Greece—divided and sub-divided by hills, mountains, and rivers—contributed to the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] On the one hand, the ancient Greeks had no doubt that they were "one people"; they had the same religion, same basic culture, and same language.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Furthermore, the Greeks were very aware of their tribal origins; Herodotus was able to extensively categorise the city-states by tribe.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Yet, although these higher-level relationships existed, they seem to have rarely had a major role in Greek politics.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The independence of the *poleis* was fiercely defended; unification was something rarely contemplated by the ancient Greeks.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Even when, during the second Persian invasion of Greece, a group of city-states allied themselves to defend Greece, the vast majority of *poleis* remained neutral, and after the Persian defeat, the allies quickly returned to infighting.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Thus, the major peculiarities of the ancient Greek political system were its fragmented nature (and that this does not particularly seem to have tribal origin), and the particular focus on urban centers within otherwise tiny states.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The peculiarities of the Greek system are further evidenced by the colonies that they set up throughout the Mediterranean, which, though they might count a certain Greek *polis* as their 'mother' (and remain sympathetic to her), were completely independent of the founding city.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Inevitably smaller *poleis* might be dominated by larger neighbors, but conquest or direct rule by another city-state appears to have been quite rare.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Instead the *poleis* grouped themselves into leagues, membership of which was in a constant state of flux.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Later in the Classical period, the leagues would become fewer and larger, be dominated by one city (particularly Athens, Sparta and Thebes); and often *poleis* would be compelled to join under threat of war (or as part of a peace treaty).
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Even after Philip II of Macedon conquered the heartlands of ancient Greece, he did not attempt to annex the territory or unify it into a new province, but compelled most of the *poleis* to join his own Corinthian League.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Initially many Greek city-states seem to have been petty kingdoms; there was often a city official carrying some residual, ceremonial functions of the king (*basileus*), e.g., the *archon basileus* in Athens.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] However, by the Archaic period and the first historical consciousness, most had already become aristocratic oligarchies.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] It is unclear exactly how this change occurred.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] For instance, in Athens, the kingship had been reduced to a hereditary, lifelong chief magistracy (*archon*) by c.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] 1050 BC; by 753 BC this had become a decennial, elected archonship, and finally an annually elected archonship by 683 BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Through each stage, more power would have been transferred to the aristocracy as a whole, and away from a single individual.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Inevitably, the domination of politics and concomitant aggregation of wealth by small groups of families was apt to cause social unrest in many *poleis*.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In many cities a tyrant (not in the modern sense of repressive autocracies), would at some point seize control and govern according to their own will; often a populist agenda would help sustain them in power.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In a system wracked with class conflict, government by a 'strongman' was often the best solution.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Athens fell under a tyranny in the second half of the 6th century BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] When this tyranny was ended, the Athenians founded the world's first democracy as a radical solution to prevent the aristocracy regaining power.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] A citizens' assembly (the *Ecclesia*), for the discussion of city policy, had existed since the reforms of Draco in 621 BC; all citizens were permitted to attend after the reforms of Solon (early 6th century), but the poorest citizens could not address the assembly or run for office.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] With the establishment of the democracy, the assembly became the *de jure* mechanism of government; all citizens had equal privileges in the assembly.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] However, non-citizens, such as metics (foreigners living in Athens) or slaves, had no political rights at all.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] After the rise of democracy in Athens, other city-states founded democracies.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] However, many retained more traditional forms of government.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] As so often in other matters, Sparta was a notable exception to the rest of Greece, ruled through the whole period by not one, but two hereditary monarchs.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Kings of Sparta belonged to the Agiads and the Eurypontids, descendants respectively of Eurysthenes and Procles.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Both dynasties' founders were believed to be twin sons of Aristodemus, a Heraclid ruler.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] However, the powers of these kings were held in check by both a council of elders (the *Gerousia*) and magistrates specifically appointed to watch over the kings (the *Ephors*).
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Only free, land-owning, native-born men could be citizens entitled to the full protection of the law in a city-state.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In most city-states, unlike the situation in Rome, social prominence did not allow special rights.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Sometimes families controlled public religious functions, but this ordinarily did not give any extra power in the government.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In Athens, the population was divided into four social classes based on wealth.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] People could change classes if they made more money.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In Sparta, all male citizens were called *homoioi*, meaning "peers".
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] However, Spartan kings, who served as the city-state's dual military and religious leaders, came from two families.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Women in Ancient Greece appear to have primarily performed domestic tasks, managed households, and borne and reared children.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Slaves had the right to have a family and own property, subject to their master's goodwill and permission, but they had no political rights.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] By 600 BC, chattel slavery had spread in Greece.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] By the 5th century BC, slaves made up one-third of the total population in some city-states.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Between 40 and 80% of the population of Classical Athens were slaves.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Slaves outside of Sparta almost never revolted because they were made up of too many nationalities and were too scattered to organize.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] However, unlike later Western culture, the ancient Greeks did not think in terms of race.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Most families owned slaves as household servants and laborers, and even poor families might have owned a few slaves.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Owners were not allowed to beat or kill their slaves.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Owners often promised to free slaves in the future to encourage slaves to work hard.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Unlike in Rome, freedmen did not become citizens.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Instead, they were mixed into the population of *metics*, which included people from foreign countries or other city-states who were officially allowed to live in the state.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] These public slaves had a larger measure of independence than slaves owned by families, living on their own and performing specialized tasks.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In Athens, public slaves were trained to look out for counterfeit coinage, while temple slaves acted as servants of the temple's deity and Scythian slaves were employed in Athens as a police force corralling citizens to political functions.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Sparta had a special type of slaves called *helots*.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Helots were Messenians enslaved en masse during the Messenian Wars by the state and assigned to families where they were forced to stay.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Helots raised food and did household chores so that women could concentrate on raising strong children while men could devote their time to training as hoplites.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Their masters treated them harshly, and helots revolted against their masters several times.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In 370/369 BC, as a result of Epaminondas' liberation of Messenia from Spartan rule, the helot system there came to an end and the helots won their freedom.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] However, it persisted in Laconia until the 2nd century BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] For most of Greek history, education was private, except in Sparta.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] During the Hellenistic period, some city-states established public schools.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Only wealthy families could afford a teacher.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Boys learned how to read, write and quote literature.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] They also learned to sing and play one musical instrument and were trained as athletes for military service.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] They studied not for a job but to become an effective citizen.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Girls also learned to read, write and do simple arithmetic so they could manage the household.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] They almost never received education after childhood.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Boys went to school at the age of seven, or went to the barracks, if they lived in Sparta.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The three types of teachings were: grammatistes for arithmetic, kitharistes for music and dancing, and Paedotribae for sports.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Boys from wealthy families attending the private school lessons were taken care of by a *paidagogos*, a household slave selected for this task who accompanied the boy during the day.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Classes were held in teachers' private houses and included reading, writing, mathematics, singing, and playing the lyre and flute.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] When the boy became 12 years old the schooling started to include sports such as wrestling, running, and throwing discus and javelin.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In Athens, some older youths attended academy for the finer disciplines such as culture, sciences, music, and the arts.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The schooling ended at age 18, followed by military training in the army usually for one or two years.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Some of Athens' greatest such schools included the Lyceum (the so-called Peripatetic school founded by Aristotle of Stageira) and the Platonic Academy (founded by Plato of Athens).
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The education system of the wealthy ancient Greeks is also called Paideia.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] At its economic height in the 5th and 4th centuries BC, the free citizenry of Classical Greece represented perhaps the most prosperous society in the ancient world, some economic historians considering Greece one of the most advanced pre-industrial economies.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In terms of wheat, wages reached an estimated 7–12 kg (15–26 lb) daily for an unskilled worker in urban Athens, 2–3 times the 3.75 kg (8.3 lb) of an unskilled rural labourer in Roman Egypt, though Greek farm incomes too were on average lower than those available to urban workers.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] At least in the Archaic period, the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece, with many competing city-states, increased the frequency of conflict but conversely limited the scale of warfare.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Unable to maintain professional armies, the city-states relied on their own citizens to fight.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] This inevitably reduced the potential duration of campaigns, as citizens would need to return to their own professions (especially in the case of, for example, farmers).
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Campaigns would therefore often be restricted to summer.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] When battles occurred, they were usually set piece and intended to be decisive.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Casualties were slight compared to later battles, rarely amounting to more than five percent of the losing side, but the slain often included the most prominent citizens and generals who led from the front.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The scale and scope of warfare in ancient Greece changed dramatically as a result of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] To fight the enormous armies of the Achaemenid Empire was effectively beyond the capabilities of a single city-state.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The eventual triumph of the Greeks was achieved by alliances of city-states (the exact composition changing over time), allowing the pooling of resources and division of labor.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Although alliances between city-states occurred before this time, nothing on this scale had been seen before.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The rise of Athens and Sparta as pre-eminent powers during this conflict led directly to the Peloponnesian War, which saw further development of the nature of warfare, strategy and tactics.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Fought between leagues of cities dominated by Athens and Sparta, the increased manpower and financial resources increased the scale and allowed the diversification of warfare.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Set-piece battles during the Peloponnesian war proved indecisive and instead there was increased reliance on attritionary strategies, naval battles and blockades and sieges.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] These changes greatly increased the number of casualties and the disruption of Greek society.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Athens owned one of the largest war fleets in ancient Greece.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] It had over 200 triremes each powered by 170 oarsmen who were seated in 3 rows on each side of the ship.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The city could afford such a large fleet—it had over 34,000 oarsmen—because it owned a lot of silver mines that were worked by slaves.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] According to Josiah Ober, Greek city-states faced approximately a one-in-three chance of destruction during the archaic and classical period.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek philosophy focused on the role of reason and inquiry.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In many ways, it had an important influence on modern philosophy, as well as modern science.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Clear unbroken lines of influence lead from ancient Greek and Hellenistic philosophers, to medieval Muslim philosophers and Islamic scientists, to the European Renaissance and Enlightenment, to the secular sciences of the modern day.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Neither reason nor inquiry began with the ancient Greeks.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Defining the difference between the Greek quest for knowledge and the quests of the elder civilizations, such as the ancient Egyptians and Babylonians, has long been a topic of study by theorists of civilization.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The first known philosophers of Greece were the pre-Socratics, who attempted to provide naturalistic, non-mythical descriptions of the world.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] They were followed by Socrates, one of the first philosophers based in Athens during its golden age whose ideas, despite being known by second-hand accounts instead of writings of his own, laid the basis of Western philosophy.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Socrates' disciple Plato, who wrote *The Republic* and established a radical difference between ideas and the concrete world, and Plato's disciple Aristotle, who wrote extensively about nature and ethics, are also immensely influential in Western philosophy to this day.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The later Hellenistic philosophy, also originating in Greece, is defined by names such as Antisthenes (cynicism), Zeno of Citium (stoicism) and Plotinus (Neoplatonism).
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek literature was poetry and was composed for performance rather than private consumption.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek poet known is Homer, although he was certainly part of an existing tradition of oral poetry.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Homer's poetry, though it was developed around the same time that the Greeks developed writing, would have been composed orally; the first poet to certainly compose their work in writing was Archilochus, a lyric poet from the mid-7th century BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Tragedy developed around the end of the archaic period, taking elements from across the pre-existing genres of late archaic poetry.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Like poetry, Greek prose had its origins in the archaic period, and the earliest writers of Greek philosophy, history, and medical literature all date to the 6th century BC.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Prose first emerged as the writing style adopted by the presocratic philosophers Anaximander and Anaximenes—though Thales of Miletus, considered the first Greek philosopher, apparently wrote nothing.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Prose as a genre reached maturity in the classical era, and the major Greek prose genres—philosophy, history, rhetoric, and dialogue—developed in this period.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period saw the literary centre of the Greek world move from Athens, where it had been in the classical period, to Alexandria.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] At the same time, other Hellenistic kings such as the Antigonids and the Attalids were patrons of scholarship and literature, turning Pella and Pergamon respectively into cultural centres.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] It was thanks to this cultural patronage by Hellenistic kings, and especially the Museum at Alexandria, that so much ancient Greek literature has survived.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Library of Alexandria, part of the Museum, had the previously unenvisaged aim of collecting together copies of all known authors in Greek.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Almost all of the surviving non-technical Hellenistic literature is poetry, and Hellenistic poetry tended to be highly intellectual, blending different genres and traditions, and avoiding linear narratives.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period also saw a shift in the ways literature was consumed—while in the archaic and classical periods literature had typically been experienced in public performance, in the Hellenistic period it was more commonly read privately.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] At the same time, Hellenistic poets began to write for private, rather than public, consumption.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] With Octavian's victory at Actium in 31 BC, Rome began to become a major centre of Greek literature, as important Greek authors such as Strabo and Dionysius of Halicarnassus came to Rome.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The period of greatest innovation in Greek literature under Rome was the "long second century" from approximately 80 AD to around 230 AD.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] This innovation was especially marked in prose, with the development of the novel and a revival of prominence for display oratory both dating to this period.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In Ancient Greek society, music was ever-present and considered a fundamental component of civilisation.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] It was an important part of public religious worship, private ceremonies such as weddings and funerals, and household entertainment.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Men sang and played music at the symposium; both men and women sang at work; and children's games involved song and dance.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek music was primarily vocal, sung either by a solo singer or a chorus, and usually accompanied by an instrument; purely instrumental music was less common.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Greeks used stringed instruments, including lyres, harps, and lutes; and wind instruments, of which the most important was the *aulos*, a reed instrument.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Percussion instruments played a relatively unimportant role supporting stringed and wind instruments, and were used in certain religious cults.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek mathematics contributed many important developments to mathematics, including the basic rules of geometry, the idea of formal mathematical proof, and discoveries in number theory, mathematical analysis, applied mathematics, and approached close to establishing integral calculus.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The discoveries of several Greek mathematicians, including Pythagoras, Euclid, and Archimedes, are still used in mathematical teaching today.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Greeks developed astronomy, which they treated as a branch of mathematics, to a highly sophisticated level.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The first geometrical, three-dimensional models to explain the apparent motion of the planets were developed in the 4th century BC by Eudoxus of Cnidus and Callippus of Cyzicus.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Their younger contemporary Heraclides Ponticus proposed that the Earth rotates around its axis.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the 3rd century BC, Aristarchus of Samos was the first to suggest a heliocentric system.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Archimedes in his treatise The Sand Reckoner revives Aristarchus' hypothesis that *"the fixed stars and the Sun remain unmoved, while the Earth revolves about the Sun on the circumference of a circle"*.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Otherwise, only fragmentary descriptions of Aristarchus' idea survive.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Eratosthenes, using the angles of shadows created at widely separated regions, estimated the circumference of the Earth with great accuracy.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the 2nd century BC Hipparchus of Nicea made a number of contributions, including the first measurement of precession and the compilation of the first star catalog in which he proposed the modern system of apparent magnitudes.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Antikythera mechanism, a device for calculating the movements of planets, dates from about 80 BC and was the first ancestor of the astronomical computer.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] It was discovered in an ancient shipwreck off the Greek island of Antikythera, between Kythera and Crete.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The device became famous for its use of a differential gear, previously believed to have been invented in the 16th century, and the miniaturization and complexity of its parts, comparable to a clock made in the 18th century.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The original mechanism is displayed in the Bronze collection of the National Archaeological Museum of Athens, accompanied by a replica.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The ancient Greeks also made important discoveries in the medical field.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Hippocrates was a physician of the Classical period, and is considered one of the most outstanding figures in the history of medicine.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] He is referred to as the "father of medicine" in recognition of his lasting contributions to the field as the founder of the Hippocratic school of medicine.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] This intellectual school revolutionized medicine in ancient Greece, establishing it as a discipline distinct from other fields that it had traditionally been associated with (notably theurgy and philosophy), thus making medicine a profession.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The art of ancient Greece has exercised an enormous influence on the culture of many countries from ancient times to the present day, particularly in the areas of sculpture and architecture.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the West, the art of the Roman Empire was largely derived from Greek models.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] In the East, Alexander the Great's conquests initiated several centuries of exchange between Greek, Central Asian and Indian cultures, resulting in Greco-Buddhist art, with ramifications as far as Japan.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Following the Renaissance in Europe, the humanist aesthetic and the high technical standards of Greek art inspired generations of European artists.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Well into the 19th century, the classical tradition derived from Greece dominated the art of the Western world.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Religion was a central part of ancient Greek life.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Though the Greeks of different cities and tribes worshipped similar gods, religious practices were not uniform and the gods were thought of differently in different places.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The Greeks were polytheistic, worshipping many gods, but as early as the 6th century BC a pantheon of twelve Olympians began to develop.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Greek religion was influenced by the practices of the Greeks' near eastern neighbours at least as early as the archaic period, and by the Hellenistic period this influence was seen in both directions.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The most important religious act in ancient Greece was animal sacrifice, most commonly of sheep and goats.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Sacrifice was accompanied by public prayer, and prayer and hymns were themselves a major part of ancient Greek religious life.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] The civilization of ancient Greece has been immensely influential on language, politics, educational systems, philosophy, science, and the arts.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] It became the *Leitkultur* of the Roman Empire to the point of marginalizing native Italic traditions.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] Via the Roman Empire, Greek culture came to be foundational to Western culture in general.
[src:ancient-greece/ancient-greece] A modern revival of Classical Greek learning took place in the Neoclassicism movement in 18th- and 19th-century Europe and the Americas.
[src:ancient-greece/anzuk] The land component of ANZUK Force was the units of 28th Commonwealth Infantry Brigade Group renamed and relocated from Malaysia to Singapore.
[src:ancient-greece/anzuk] Sea and Air components did not wear any of the patches as they remained under national command and were only attached to NZUK command on an as required basis.
[src:ancient-greece/anzuk] By 1973 the political climate in Australia and the United Kingdom had changed and it was deemed that ANZUK should be disbanded.
[src:ancient-greece/anzuk] Rear Admiral Wells, the First ANZUK commander who established the Force, had the task of planning the run-down phase and handing over to his successor Air Vice Marshal Richard Gordon Wakeford, to follow through.
[src:ancient-greece/anzuk] Australia would be retaining a presence in Butterworth in Malaysia and the United Kingdom had decided to withdraw all its forces east of Suez.
[src:ancient-greece/anzuk] It was in New Zealand's interest to retain a force in southeast Asia, so on 30 January 1974 New Zealand Force South East Asia was formed, taking under its command all the New Zealand units formerly part of ANZUK.
[src:ancient-greece/anzuk] Over the course of 1974 the integrated units which made up the ANZUK were gradually disbanded and replaced by national units.
[src:ancient-greece/anzuk] On 31 January 1974 ceased to exist, followed on 16 December 1974 with the disbanding of the Naval and Air Headquarters and their assets reverted to their respective national command and what remained of the United Kingdom's land component forces became the 28th (UK) Infantry Brigade.
[src:ancient-greece/anzuk] Taking several years for the Australian and United Kingdom units to draw down and withdraw, it was not until 1977 that NZFORSEA was the sole remaining foreign presence in Singapore.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The **Australia, New Zealand, United States Security Treaty** (**ANZUS** or **ANZUS Treaty**) is a collective security agreement between Australia, New Zealand, and the United States that was signed in 1951, and from which New Zealand has been partially suspended since 1986.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] It firstly recommits the parties to the purposes of the United Nations, prohibiting the use of force or threats except in self-defence.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] It also provides for a council of the signatories foreign ministers, in which the implementation of the treaty can be discussed.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The treaty was one of a series that the United States formed in the 1949–1955 era as part of its collective response to the threat of communism during the Cold War.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] New Zealand was suspended from ANZUS in 1986 as it initiated a nuclear-free zone in its territorial waters.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] In late 2012, the United States lifted a 26-year-old ban on visits by New Zealand warships to US Department of Defense and US Coast Guard bases around the world.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The treaty was previously a full three-way defence pact, but was disrupted following a dispute between New Zealand and the United States in 1984 over visiting rights for ships and submarines capable of carrying nuclear arms or nuclear-powered ships of the US Navy to New Zealand ports.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The treaty has lapsed between the United States and New Zealand, but remains separately in force between both of those states and Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] In 2000, the United States opened its ports to the Royal New Zealand Navy once again, and under the presidency of Bill Clinton in the US and the government of Helen Clark in New Zealand, the countries have since reestablished bilateral cooperation on defence and security.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] While ANZUS is commonly recognised to have split in 1984, the Australia–US alliance remains in full force.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Heads of defence of one or both states often have joined the annual ministerial meetings, which are supplemented by consultations between the US Combatant Commander Pacific and the Australian Chief of Defence Force.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] There are also regular civilian and military consultations between the two governments at lower levels.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Annual meetings to discuss ANZUS defence matters take place between the United States Secretaries of Defense and State and the Australian Ministers of Defence and Foreign Affairs, and are known by the acronym AUSMIN.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Unlike the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), ANZUS has no integrated defence structure or dedicated forces.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Nevertheless, Australia and the United States conduct a variety of joint activities.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] These include military exercises ranging from naval and landing exercises at the task-group level to battalion-level special forces training, assigning officers to each other's armed services, and standardising equipment and operational doctrine.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The two countries also operate several joint-defence facilities in Australia, mainly ground stations for spy satellite, and signals intelligence espionage in Southeast and East Asia as part of the ECHELON network.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] During the 2010s, New Zealand and the US resumed a close relationship, although it is unclear whether the revived partnership falls under the aegis of the 1951 trilateral treaty.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The Wellington Declaration of 2010 defined a "strategic partnership" between New Zealand and the US, and New Zealand joined the biennial Rim of the Pacific military exercise off Hawaii in 2012, for the first time since 1984.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The US prohibition on New Zealand ships making port at US bases was lifted after the 2012 exercise.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Following the fall of Singapore and the decline of British power in Asia, Australia began to search for other partners to ensure its security.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Australia and New Zealand also felt threatened by the possibility of a resurgent Japan and the spread of communism to their North.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Percy Spender, Australia's minister for external affairs, sought a broader Pacific security agreement in 1950 which would include Australia, the UK, other Commonwealth countries and the United States.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The latter's participation was essential, with Spencer stating the agreement "would be meaningless without the United States".
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] At this point however, both the UK and the US were uninterested in such an agreement, with both seeking to limit their engagement with Asia.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The beginning of the Korean War in mid-1950 changed American views.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Australia committed to the Korean War before the United Kingdom and continued to further court the Americans.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The United States was initially reluctant, but the need to strengthen the West against communism grew with the communist victory in the Chinese Civil War in 1949 and the 1950–1953 Korean War.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The treaty allayed antipodean fears that such a peace would allow Japan to threaten them again.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The United States was initially reluctant, with the president instead offering an informal guarantee of protection.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Instead, the text of the treaty mirrored the text of the Monroe Doctrine which stated that attacks on the American continent would be seen as "dangerous to its own peace and security".
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The resulting treaty was concluded at San Francisco on 1 September 1951, and entered into force on 29 April 1952.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The treaty itself was not a source of debate for over 30 years, with New Zealand participating as part of the British Commonwealth Forces in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency, followed by the Indonesia–Malaysia confrontation, and directly as part of ANZUS in the Vietnam War.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The Vietnam War was the first conflict New Zealand entered that did not involve the British or any other Commonwealth countries outside of Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] As an ANZUS member New Zealand contributed military and non military assistance to the United States war effort in Vietnam from 1963 until 1975.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] New Zealand and Australian combat forces were withdrawn in 1972 and New Zealand non-military medical aid continued until 1975.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] In 1983, the Reagan Administration approached Australia with proposals for testing the new generation of American intercontinental ballistic missiles, the MX missile.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] American test ranges in the Pacific were insufficient for testing the new long-range missiles and the United States military wished to use the Tasman Sea as a target area.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Australian Prime Minister Malcolm Fraser of the Liberal Party had agreed to provide monitoring sites near Sydney for this purpose.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] However, in 1985, the newly elected Prime Minister Bob Hawke, of the Labor Party, withdrew Australia from the testing programme, sparking criticism from the Reagan Administration.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Hawke had been pressured into doing so by the left-wing faction of the Labor Party, which opposed the proposed MX missile test in the Tasman Sea.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The Labor left-wing faction also strongly sympathized with the New Zealand Fourth Labour Government's anti-nuclear policy and supported a South Pacific Nuclear Free Zone.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] To preserve its joint Australian-US military communications facilities, the Reagan Administration also had to assure the Hawke Government that those installations would not be used in the Strategic Defense Initiative project, which the Australian Labor Party strongly opposed.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Despite these disagreements, the Hawke Labor Government still remained supportive of the ANZUS security treaty.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] It also did not support its New Zealand counterpart's ban on nuclear-armed and nuclear-powered ships.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Following the ANZUS Split in February 1985, the Australian government also endorsed the Reagan Administration's plans to cancel trilateral military exercises and to postpone the ANZUS foreign ministers conference.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] However, it still continued to maintain bilateral military ties and continued to share intelligence information with New Zealand.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Unlike New Zealand, Australia continued to allow US warships to visit its ports and to participate in joint military exercises with the United States.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] In 1985, the nature of the ANZUS alliance changed significantly.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Due to a current of anti-nuclear sentiment within New Zealand, tension had long been present between ANZUS members as the United States is a declared nuclear power.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] France, a naval power and a declared nuclear power, had been conducting nuclear tests on South Pacific Islands.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Following the victory of the New Zealand Labour Party in election in 1984, Prime Minister David Lange barred nuclear-powered or nuclear-armed ships from using New Zealand ports or entering New Zealand waters.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Reasons given were the dangers of nuclear weapons, continued French nuclear testing in the South Pacific, and opposition to US president Ronald Reagan's policy of aggressively confronting the Soviet Union.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Given that the United States Navy had a policy of deliberate ambiguity during the Cold War and refused to confirm or deny the presence of nuclear weapons aboard its warships and support ships, these laws essentially refused access to New Zealand ports for all United States Navy vessels.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] In February 1985, a port-visit request by the United States for the guided-missile destroyer USS *Buchanan* was refused by New Zealand, as the *Buchanan* was capable of launching RUR-5 ASROC nuclear depth bombs.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] As this occurred after the government unofficially invited the United States to send a ship, the refusal of access was interpreted by the United States as a deliberate slight.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] According to opinion polls taken before the 1984 election, only 30 per cent of New Zealanders supported visits by US warships with a clear majority of 58 per cent opposed, and over 66 per cent of the population lived in locally declared nuclear-free zones.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The crisis made front-page headlines for weeks in many American newspapers.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] David Lange did not withdraw New Zealand from ANZUS, although his government's policy led to the US's decision to suspend its treaty obligations to New Zealand.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] An opinion poll in New Zealand in 1991, showed 54% of those sampled preferred to let the treaty lapse rather than accept visits again by nuclear-armed or nuclear-powered vessels.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] This law effectively made the entire country a nuclear-free zone.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Despite the ANZUS split, US Secretary of State George P.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Shultz maintained that the ANZUS structure was still in place, should NZ decide in the future to reverse its anti-nuclear policy and return to a fully operational defence relationship with the US.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] President Reagan also maintained in *NSDD 193* (National Security Decision Directive) that New Zealand still remained a "friend, but not an ally".
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] On 10 July 1985, agents of the French Directorate-General for External Security bombed the Greenpeace protest vessel *Rainbow Warrior* in Auckland, causing one death.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The lack of condemnation by Western leaders to this violation of a friendly state's sovereignty caused a great deal of change in New Zealand's foreign and defence policy, and strengthened domestic opposition to the military application of nuclear technology in any form.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] New Zealand distanced itself from its traditional ally, the United States, and built relationships with small South Pacific countries, while retaining its good relations with Australia, and, to a lesser extent, the United Kingdom.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The suspension of New Zealand in ANZUS has had significant effect on New Zealand–United States relations and on New Zealand domestic policy.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The anti-nuclear policy has been a part of New Zealand political culture for years now.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] However, that has not stopped United States politicians from trying to change the policy.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Australia and New Zealand both provided military units, including special forces and naval ships, in support of the US-led "Operation Enduring Freedom" for support for anti-Taliban forces in response to the 11 September 2001 terrorist attacks.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Providing 1,550 troops, Australia was the largest non-NATO contributor of military personnel in Afghanistan.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] In response to the War in Afghanistan, New Zealand sent transport aircraft, maritime patrol aircraft, and frigates to the Persian Gulf, and sent a very small number of soldiers, SAS soldiers, medical and assorted and peace-keeping forces to Afghanistan in 2001.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Despite Prime Minister Helen Clark being openly critical of American justifications for the 2003 Iraq war, New Zealand sent engineer troops to Iraq following the 2003 invasion.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] These troops were however officially engaged in reconstruction under UN Security Council Resolution 1483 and were non-combatant.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Between 1999 and 2003, the armed forces of Australia and New Zealand deployed together in a large scale operation in East Timor, to prevent pro-Indonesian militia from overturning a vote for independence on the region.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The United States provided only limited logistical support but the USS *Mobile Bay* provided air defence for the initial entry operation.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The operation was taken over by the United Nations.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] One topic that became prominent in the 2000s was the implications in the case of a hypothetical attack by the People's Republic of China against Taiwan, who would likely receive American support.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] While Australia has strong cultural and economic ties with the United States, it also has an increasingly important trade relationship with mainland China.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] In August 2004, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer implied in Beijing that the treaty would likely not apply to that situation, but he was quickly corrected by Prime Minister John Howard.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Annual bilateral meetings between the US Secretary of State and the Australian Foreign Minister replaced annual meetings of the ANZUS Council of Foreign Ministers.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The first bilateral meeting was held in Canberra in 1985.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] At the second meeting, in San Francisco in 1986, the United States announced that it was suspending its treaty security obligations to New Zealand pending the restoration of port access.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Subsequent bilateral Australia–US Ministerial (AUSMIN) meetings have alternated between Australia and the United States.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Code § 2321k, United States president Bill Clinton, designated New Zealand as a major non-NATO ally, effectively recognizing New Zealand not only as a friend but also an ally.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The alliance engenders some political controversy in Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Particularly after Australian involvement in the 2003 Iraq war, some quarters of Australian society have called for a re-evaluation of the relationship between the two nations.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Nonetheless, the alliance enjoyed broad support during the Cold War and continues to enjoy broad support in Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] One commentator in Australia has argued that the treaty should be re-negotiated in the context of terrorism, the modern role of the United Nations and as a purely US–Australian alliance.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Australia is also a contributor to the National Missile Defense system.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] In May 2006, US assistant secretary of state for east asia and pacific affairs Christopher Hill described the New Zealand anti-nuclear issue as "a bit of a relic", and signalled that the US wanted a closer defence relationship with New Zealand.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] He also praised New Zealand's involvement in Afghanistan and reconstruction in Iraq.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] "Rather than trying to change each other's minds on the nuclear issue, which is a bit of a relic, I think we should focus on things we can make work" he told an Australian newspaper.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] While there were signs of the nuclear dispute between the US and NZ thawing out, pressure from the United States increased in 2006 with US trade officials linking the repeal of the ban of American nuclear ships from New Zealand's ports to a potential free trade agreement between the two countries.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] On 4 February 2008, US trade representative Susan Schwab announced that the United States would join negotiations with four Asia–Pacific countries: Brunei, Chile, New Zealand and Singapore to be known as the "P-4".
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] These countries already had a FTA called the Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership and the United States was looking to become involved in the "vitally important emerging Asia-Pacific region".
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] A number of US-based organisations supported the negotiations including, but not limited to, the United States Chamber of Commerce, National Association of Manufacturers, National Foreign Trade Council, Emergency Committee for American Trade and Coalition of Service Industries.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] In 2010, the United States and New Zealand signed the Wellington Declaration in Wellington, New Zealand, during a three-day visit by US secretary of state Hillary Clinton.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The signing of the declaration ended the ANZUS dispute of the previous 25 years.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] It was later revealed the US and New Zealand had resumed military co-operation in eight areas in 2007.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] On 16 November 2011, US president Obama and Australian prime minister Julia Gillard met in Canberra, Australia, to announce plans for a sustained new American presence on Australian soil.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] 2,500 American troops are to be deployed to Darwin, Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] New Zealand and the United States signed the Washington Declaration on 19 June 2012 "to promote and strengthen closer bilateral defense and security cooperation".
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The Royal New Zealand Navy (RNZN) invited the United States Navy to send a vessel to participate in the RNZN's 75th Birthday Celebrations in Auckland over the weekend of 19–21 November 2016.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] The guided-missile destroyer USS *Sampson* became the first US warship to visit New Zealand in 33 years.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] New Zealand prime minister John Key granted approval for the ship's visit under the New Zealand Nuclear Free Zone, Disarmament, and Arms Control Act 1987, which requires that the Prime Minister has to be satisfied that any visiting ship is not nuclear armed or powered.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] Following the 7.8 magnitude Kaikōura earthquake on 14 November 2016 the *Sampson* and other naval ships from Australia, Canada, Japan and Singapore were diverted to proceed directly to Kaikōura to provide humanitarian assistance.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] In late 2021 Australia, the UK and the USA signed the AUKUS agreement, a trilateral security partnership between Australia, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:ancient-greece/anzus] New Zealand did not participate and any nuclear submarines developed under the pact will be banned from New Zealand waters under their existing nuclear restrictions.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] AUKUS is widely seen as a response to the perception among its members that the People's Republic of China poses a threat to the Indo-Pacific region.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The Chinese government said, when the partnership was announced, that it risked "severely damaging regional peace" and had a "cold-war mentality".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] A direct result of the creation of the partnership was Australia's controversial cancellation of a French-Australian submarine contract worth €56 billion (A$90 billion).
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The Australian government only gave the French government a few hours' notice of this before the public announcement of AUKUS.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The Australian government agreed to a €555 million (US$584 million) compensation settlement with French defence contractor Naval Group.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In 2009, two years after the start of the project to replace the Royal Australian Navy's conventionally-powered *Collins*-class submarines, the Australian Defence White Paper stated: "The Government has ruled out nuclear propulsion for these submarines".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The design was based on the latest French nuclear-powered attack submarine, the Barracuda class, which required converting the nuclear propulsion to conventional propulsion.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Another difference was that Australia chose to equip it with a United States Navy combat system and torpedo with Lockheed Martin Australia selected to integrate them into the design.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Australia typically requires that part of their vessels be built there, which increases the cost.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In this case it corresponded to 60 per cent of the contract value, with France handling the technology transfer.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In 2019, Australia signed a strategic partnership agreement with Naval Group to design and construct twelve submarines to be built in Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] However, the project was beset by delays and cost overruns, leading to uncertainty and tension behind the scenes.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The revised cost, including inflation during the length of the program, was A$90 billion (€56 billion).
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In February 2021, an initial design plan was rejected as being too expensive, and Naval Group were given until September to improve their proposal.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] At a Senate inquiry in early June 2021, with delays ongoing, Defence Secretary Greg Moriarty revealed under questioning that he had considered making contingency plans if the French project was to fail, admitting that there had been ongoing problems for over a year.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Two weeks later, Australian prime minister Scott Morrison met French president Emmanuel Macron in Paris and expressed concern about the project going off track, to which Macron replied that France was giving "full and complete" commitment and would proceed "further and faster if possible".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Less than three weeks later, Australia decided to publicly cancel the contract with Naval Group for the *Attack* class submarines despite having already spent about A$2.4 billion on the French project.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] It was expected that Australia would have to pay hundreds of millions of euros in penalties for cancelling the contract.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The contract contained "control gates" with "off-ramps" at which point Australia could withdraw from the contract.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The Australian Department of Defence wrote to Naval Group on the same day the security partnership was announced.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The French Ministry of Defence claim the department told them that "they were satisfied with the submarine's achievable performance and with the progress of the program." Naval Group said that Australia "terminated the contract for convenience".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Morrison said that Australia now required a nuclear-powered submarine which has clear advantages of greater endurance, speed, power, stealth and carrying capacity than a conventionally-powered submarine, based on changes in the strategic situation in the Indo-Pacific.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] However, Johnson later told parliament that the move was not intended to be "adversarial towards any other power".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] United States secretary of state Antony Blinken and United States secretary of defense Lloyd Austin said that Australia did not have any "reciprocal requirements" as a consequence of the US sharing nuclear submarine propulsion technology such as Australia hosting intermediate-range missiles.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Under the partnership, the US and UK will share nuclear propulsion technology with Australia, as they have done with each other since 1958 under the US–UK Mutual Defence Agreement.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The Royal Australian Navy (RAN) will acquire at least eight nuclear-powered submarines armed with conventional weapons.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The basic design and key technologies will be decided by the Australian Nuclear-Powered Submarine Task Force an 18-month Department of Defence research project headed by Vice Admiral Jonathan Mead, begun in September 2021 with assistance from the US and UK.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Australia will extend the life of its *Collins* class submarines that the *Attack* class was due to replace and may consider leasing or buying nuclear-powered submarines from the US or the UK in the interim until the delivery of its future nuclear powered submarines.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Also in the interim, Australian Defence Minister Peter Dutton said that Australia will have regular visits by US and UK nuclear-powered submarines.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Australia considered purchasing French nuclear submarines which use nuclear reactors fuelled by low-enriched uranium at less than 6%.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] However, French reactor designs have to be refuelled every ten years, and Australia does not have a civil nuclear capability with nuclear energy prohibited.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In contrast, American and British designs power the submarines for the expected life of the submarines using nuclear reactors fuelled by highly enriched uranium (HEU) at 93% enrichment.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Currently, six countries have nuclear submarines, the five permanent members of the UN Security Council (China, France, Russia, the United Kingdom and the United States) and India.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The New York Times reported that Australia will probably buy HEU from the US for the nuclear reactor that powers the submarine.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The United States' naval reactors are all pressurized water reactors (PWR).
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The latest UK propulsion system is the Rolls-Royce PWR3 that will power the Royal Navy's (RN) new *Dreadnought*-class submarines currently being built and is "based on a US design but using UK reactor technology".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] US officials have said that sharing nuclear propulsion technology with Australia is a "one-off" and that they have no "intention of extending this to other countries".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] South Korea, also a US treaty ally, has had ambitions to acquire nuclear-powered submarines since 2017 and was reportedly refused US assistance in September 2020 because of nuclear non-proliferation.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] On 22 November 2021, Australia, the US and the UK signed the *Exchange of Naval Nuclear Propulsion Information Agreement* (ENNPIA) treaty.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The treaty permits the disclosure of information by the US and the UK to Australia and its use.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The US is restricted by the Atomic Energy Act of 1946 from sharing information without an agreement and the UK is also restricted by the 1958 US-UK Mutual Defence Agreement unless authorised.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The treaty was considered in Australia by the Parliament's Joint Standing Committee on Treaties, in the UK by the Parliament and in the US by Congress.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The ENNPIA treaty entered into force on 8 February 2022.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] On 31 August 2022, the UK announced that Australian submariners would receive training aboard *Astute*-class submarines.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] On 13 March 2023, AUKUS announced that a new nuclear powered submarine class would be built in the UK and Australia to be called the SSN-AUKUS, also known as the SSN-A.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The US intends to sell Australia three nuclear-powered *Virginia* class submarines, subject to congressional approval, to ensure there is no capability gap as the *Collins* class submarines are retired, with the potential to sell up to two more if needed.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] RAN personnel will be embedded in the RN and USN to receive nuclear training and at UK and US submarine industrial bases.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The SSN-AUKUS class will based on the UK SSNR design already under development.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The RN is planned to receive its first SSN-AUKUS class submarine as early as the late 2030s.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The RAN is planned to receive their first submarine in the early 2040s.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Australia will reportedly build five SSN-AUKUS submarines.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The RAN is planned to receive their first *Virginia* class submarine from the US in the early 2030s.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The Australian Submarine Agency was established on 1 July 2023.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] It has the role of managing the Australian nuclear submarine program, and includes personnel posted to the UK and US.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Lincoln Reifsteck USN, the USN's AUKUS integration and acquisition program manager, talked at the Naval Submarine League's annual symposium.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] He said that, in 2032 and 2035, the US will sell to Australia in-service Block IV *Virginia* class submarines, the first of which was commissioned in 2020, and the final will likely commission around 2026.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Thus, Australia would receive submarines with between six and 15 years' worth of use, out of their designed service life of 33 years.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] He also said that the US would sell a new Block VII boat to Australia in 2038, the Block VIIs being the original *Virginia* class length without the Virginia Payload Module, set to begin construction in FY2029.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In August 2024, Australian prime minister Anthony Albanese, made undisclosed "political commitments" with its AUKUS partners in an agreement for the transfer of naval nuclear technology to Australia, sparking concerns about the potential for high-level radioactive waste to be stored in the country.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The White House confirmed that Australia, the UK, and the US reached a significant milestone in their cooperation, essential for Australia's future nuclear-powered submarine capabilities.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Despite assurances from the government, critics, including the Greens, warned of possible loopholes that could lead to uranium enrichment and radioactive waste management in Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] On 1 June 2025, the UK government announced that it will build up to twelve SSN-AUKUS submarines to replace the Royal Navy's seven *Astute-*class attack submarines from the late 2030s.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The announcement also said that there will be a major expansion of industrial capability at BAE Systems Submarines at Barrow and at Rolls-Royce Submarines at Derby, with a new boat scheduled to be built every eighteen months.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] On 26 July 2025, the UK and Australian governments signed the **Geelong Treaty**, a 50-year bilateral defence agreement to facilitate bilateral cooperation on the construction of Australia's SSN-AUKUS submarines.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] On 30 May 2026, at an AUKUS Defence Minister's Meeting held in Singapore it was announced that the third *Virginia-*class boat that Australia is planned to receive will now be an in-service Block IV boat the same as the first two.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] This will simplify fleet training and maintenance for Australia and save them significant costs.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] AUKUS Pillar 2 encompasses a wide array of activities (including many commonly referred to by the US Department of Defense as international armaments cooperation).
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] There may include information and personnel exchange, cooperative research, development, testing, and evaluation, and joint production.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In contrast to Pillar 1 activities, which will take decades to deliver results, Pillar 2 is likely to produce more immediate capability improvements.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Undersea capabilities, in the context of AUKUS, refer to systems and technologies that operate underwater but are not crewed submarines.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The Defence Minister's meeting on 30 May 2026 announced that the first signature project of Pillar 2 would be cutting-edge sensors, payloads and weapons systems for UUVs with delivery to commence in 2027.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] As part of the Quantum Technologies working group, the AUKUS nations have established the AUKUS Quantum Arrangement (AQuA), an initiative to coordinate U.S., British, and Australian RDT&E efforts concerning quantum technologies.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Initial AQuA efforts were expected to focus on developing alternate solutions for position, navigation, and timing (similar to current Global Positioning System capability) through trials and experimentation through 2025.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The announcement of AUKUS included the stated aim of improving "joint capabilities and interoperability.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] We've always been interoperable, but this aims at much more.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] From artificial intelligence to advanced technology the US, UK and Australia will now be able to cost save by increasing platform sharing and innovation costs.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] *Engineering & Technology* also pointed to the March 2021 statement of the US National Security Commission on AI, of the imperative to intensify local efforts but also "rally our closest allies and partners to defend and compete in the coming era of AI-accelerated competition and conflict".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Under the partnership, the three countries will cooperate to accelerate development of hypersonic missiles and defence against such missiles.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Hypersonic and counter-hypersonic cooperation was one of four additional areas of cooperation announced on 5 April 2022.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Australia and the US have been cooperating on the development of hypersonic missiles since 2020 after signing an agreement to "flight test full-size prototype hypersonic cruise missiles" under the Southern Cross Integrated Flight Research Experiment (SCIFiRE).
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In addition, the U.S., British, and Australian governments have established a number of initiatives designed to support Pillar 2 efforts as a whole, such as the AUKUS Advanced Capabilities Industry Forum and the AUKUS Defense Investors Network.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Since the announcement of "Pillar II" of AUKUS, there has been persistent speculation that Japan will eventually join the partnership; American Ambassador to Japan Rahm Emanuel wrote that Japan was "about to become the first additional Pillar II partner" in *The Wall Street Journal* on 3 April 2024.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] On 7 April 2024, the *Financial Times* reported that AUKUS defence ministers will announce on 8 April 2024 that they will launch talks related to the expansion of Pillar II of the alliance.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In September 2024, the leaders of Australia, the UK and the US issued a joint statement announcing that AUKUS partners and Japan were exploring opportunities to improve interoperability of their maritime autonomous systems as an initial area of cooperation.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] New Zealand has agreed to officially explore the potential benefits of joining Pillar 2.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In March 2023, New Zealand's defence minister Andrew Little said New Zealand had been offered the opportunity to discuss joining AUKUS for the non-submarine co-operation areas.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] New Zealand has indicated it was "willing to explore" the proposal.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In July 2023, US Secretary of State Antony Blinken told New Zealand reporters that the “door is open” for New Zealand, as well as other countries, to join the security partnership.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In December 2023, following the formation of a new government, Prime Minister Christopher Luxon said that New Zealand was open to joining the non-nuclear pillar of the AUKUS agreement during a state visit to Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In February 2024, Australia agreed to brief New Zealand on Pillar 2 developments following a joint bilateral meeting between Australian and New Zealand foreign and defence ministers in Melbourne.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Australian Defence Minister Richard Marles confirmed that Australia would send officials to brief their New Zealand counterparts on Pillar 2.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The four ministers also issued a joint statement expressing concerns about human rights violations in Xinjiang, Tibet and Hong Kong.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In response to the joint Australian-NZ bilateral meeting, the Chinese Embassy in Wellington issued a statement deploring critical statements about China's internal affairs and describing AUKUS as "counter to the letter and spirit of the international nuclear non-proliferation regime".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In September 2024, the leaders of Australia, the UK and the US issued a joint statement announcing that they were consulting with Canada, New Zealand, and South Korea to identify possibilities for collaboration on advanced capabilities under AUKUS Pillar II.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty allows non-nuclear-weapon states to produce the highly enriched uranium for naval reactor fuel.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Nevertheless, the agreement to transfer US or UK nuclear submarine technology including possibly highly enriched uranium has been described as an act of nuclear proliferation, and has been criticised by scholars and politicians.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In the *Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists*, scholar Sébastien Philippe criticised AUKUS and wrote "we can now expect the proliferation of very sensitive military nuclear technology in the coming years, with literally tons of new nuclear materials under loose or no international safeguards".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Acton of the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace wrote that "the nonproliferation implications of the AUKUS submarine deal are both negative and serious.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] For Australia to operate nuclear-powered submarines, it will have to become the first non-nuclear-weapon state to exercise a loophole that allows it to remove nuclear material from the inspection system of the International Atomic Energy Agency.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] I have no real concerns that Australia will misuse this material itself, but I am concerned that this removal will set a damaging precedent.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Australia and Brazil would be the first countries without nuclear weapons to have nuclear-powered submarines.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] This would not apply in the case of Brazil because the reactor will use low enriched uranium at 7% concentration.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] 20% is the minimum level required to make a nuclear weapon.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Former Labor prime minister Paul Keating condemned the deal, saying "This arrangement would witness a further dramatic loss of Australian sovereignty, as material dependency on the United States robbed Australia of any freedom or choice in any engagement Australia may deem appropriate".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Former Labor prime minister Kevin Rudd warned against overly obtrusive criticism of China and recommended that Australia focus on quietly improving military capability.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Former Liberal prime minister Malcolm Turnbull, who had signed the original deal for the *Attack* class submarines called the decision to scrap the deal "an appalling episode in Australia's international affairs and the consequences of it will endure to our disadvantage for a very long time".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] He called the actions of his successor as deceitful and that it would damage Australia as foreign nations would no longer be able to trust Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Abbott said that Australia would be safer as a result, and cited China's increasing naval firepower as a justification for the deal.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The Australian defence minister at the time, Peter Dutton, responded by saying that Australia wanted peace and stability and "an opportunity for Indonesia, Vietnam and Sri Lanka and Korea to continue to develop".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Dutton further dismissed "outbursts from China" and said that Australia was a "proud democracy" committed to "enduring peace and this collaboration makes it a safer region ... no amount of propaganda can dismiss the facts".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Australian Greens leader Adam Bandt criticised the deal, saying that it escalates tensions in the region and "makes Australia less safe".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Prime Minister at the time, Boris Johnson, said that the deal would create "hundreds of high-skilled jobs" and "preserve security and stability around the world" but said that the relationship with France was "rock solid".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Conservative MP Tom Tugendhat said: "After years of bullying and trade hostility, and watching regional neighbours like the Philippines see encroachment into their waters, Australia didn't have a choice, and nor did the US or UK [to make the deal]".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Former prime minister Theresa May questioned whether the UK would be forced into a war with China should Taiwan be invaded.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Johnson responded to French anger on 21 September by saying "I just think it's time for some of our dearest friends around the world to prenez un grip about this and donnez-moi un break"; the latter being broken French for "get a grip and give me a break".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In 2026, the Defence Select Committee inquiry on AUKUS found that the political leadership of the programme had faded and that the UK commitment to *Astute*-class submarine visits to Australia had placed severe pressure on the overstretched Royal Navy.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] Responsibility for AUKUS had been transferred from the Cabinet Office to the Ministry of Defence, though the view that Prime Ministerial leadership would be important to maintaining the political impetus to deliver AUKUS was reported.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] The MOD had forecast that the UK nuclear workforce (defence plus civil) will need to increase by 40,000 by 2030 to support AUKUS and the wider demands on the Defence Nuclear Enterprise.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] To 2026, the UK government had committed £16 billion to developing AUKUS: long lead components for SSN-AUKUS, BAE and Rolls-Royce plant upgrades, and the Rolls-Royce nuclear reactors for submarines.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] It noted that trilateral progress on advanced technology under Pillar 2 had been inadequate and was losing credibility.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] President Joe Biden stated that the deal was a way to "address both the current strategic environment in the (Indo-Pacific) region and how it may evolve".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] After a call between the French and US presidents, the White House acknowledged the crisis could have been averted if there had been open consultations between allies.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] It was agreed the process would continue in such manner.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p01] In June 2025, the United States Department of Defense launched a review to inform whether to modify or cancel the AUKUS agreement with Australia and the United Kingdom, after a push by the Under Secretary of Defense for Policy, Elbridge Colby.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] On 12 April 2022, *Sankei Shimbun* reported that the United States, United Kingdom, and Australia were inquiring about Japan's participation in the security framework of AUKUS.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] The newspaper added that the aim of said negotiations was related to the incorporation of Japanese hypersonic weapon development and the strengthening of electronic warfare capabilities.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] The US denied inviting Japan into the security alliance, with Jen Psaki stating that Sankei Shimbun's report was "inaccurate".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] This was followed by another denial from Hirokazu Matsuno, the Japanese chief cabinet secretary.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] On 10 December 2022, Australia's Minister for Defence announced their desire for Japan to join the partnership.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] On 14 March 2023, Japanese prime minister Kishida Fumio expressed his support for Australia's planned acquisition of US-made nuclear-powered submarines under the AUKUS partnership.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] The French government received official notification from Australia that the *Attack* class submarine project was to be cancelled only a few hours before it was publicly announced.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] *Le Monde* reported that the original cost of the project in 2016 was €35 billion of which €8 billion (A$12 billion) was to go to French companies.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] The project was reportedly going to employ 4,000 people in France over six years at Naval Group and its 200 subcontractors.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] The French government was angered by both the cancellation of the *Attack* class submarine project and not being made aware of the negotiations that led to the AUKUS agreement.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] In a joint statement, French foreign minister Jean-Yves Le Drian and armed forces minister Florence Parly expressed disappointment at Australia's decision to abandon their joint submarine program with France.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] On 31 October 2021, at the G20 summit in Rome, Macron was asked whether he thought that PM Morrison lied about the French submarine contract, to which Macron responded "I don't think, I know".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] The French Ambassador also criticised Morrison on the basis that he lied about the former contract.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] Le Drian further stated in a radio interview that the contract termination was a "stab in the back".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] On 17 September, France recalled its ambassadors from Australia and the US, Jean-Pierre Thébault and Philippe Étienne respectively.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] Despite tension in the past, France had never before withdrawn its ambassador to the United States.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] In a statement, Le Drian said that the "exceptional decision is justified by the exceptional gravity of the [AUKUS] announcements" and that the snap cancellation of the submarine contract "constitute[d] unacceptable behaviour between allies and partners".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] French president Emmanuel Macron has not commented but is reported to have been "furious" about the turn of events.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] In response to questions about the Australia-EU trade deal currently being negotiated, French secretary of state for European affairs Clément Beaune stated that he doesn't see how France can trust Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] Arnaud Danjean, a French MEP, said that "Australians can expect more than a delay in concluding the Free Trade Agreement with the EU".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] French Lowy Institute policy analyst Hervé Lemahieu said the diplomatic damage from the cancellation will take years to repair and leave a lasting legacy of mistrust".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] After a call between the French and US presidents, the French ambassador returned to the US on 30 September.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] Beaune described the United Kingdom as a junior partner and vassal of the United States due to the partnership, saying in an interview: "Our British friends explained to us they were leaving the EU to create Global Britain.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] We can see that this is a return into the American lap and a form of accepted vassalisation." Le Drian stated that "We have recalled our ambassadors to [Canberra and Washington] to re-evaluate the situation.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] So there is no need to bring our ambassador back to explain." A Franco-British defence summit was cancelled.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] Some opposition politicians in France, such as Xavier Bertrand, Jordan Bardella, and Fabien Roussel, criticised the French government and demanded that France leave NATO, with Christian Jacob as well as demanding a parliamentary inquiry.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] A foreign ministers meeting between France, Germany, the UK, and the US had been postponed, and a ministerial meeting between Australia, France, and India was cancelled.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] France however, contacted India to talk about strengthening their cooperation in the Indo-Pacific.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] France's foreign commerce minister declined a meeting with his Australian counterpart.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] French president Macron said that Europe needs to stop being naïve when it comes to defending its interests and build its own military capacity.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] Following the ousting of Scott Morrison's government after the 2022 Australian federal election, the new Labor government led by Prime Minister Anthony Albanese agreed to a €555 million (US$584 million) settlement with French defence contractor Naval Group.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] In response, French defence minister Lecornu said that France aims to rebuild its relationship with Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] In addition, Albanese announced plans to travel to France to reset bilateral relations between the two countries.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] The exclusion of France from AUKUS has been conceptualised within the longue durée of the fractious relationship between France and the Anglosphere, potentially reducing scope for coordination in the Indo-Pacific in the short term.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] Zhao also said "The three countries should discard the Cold War zero-sum mentality and narrow geopolitical perspective".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] Spokesperson Hua Chunying said "China is firmly opposed to the US, the UK and Australia's malicious exploitation of loopholes in the Nuclear non-proliferation treaty and the International Atomic Energy Agency safeguards mechanism".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] It further told Australia to avoid "provocation" or else China would "certainly punish it with no mercy", and concluded "Thus, Australian troops are also most likely to be the first batch of western soldiers to waste their lives in the South China Sea".
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] The PRC ambassador to France Lu Shaye urged the new alliance to fulfill their nuclear non proliferation obligations and said Asia-Pacific needs jobs, not submarines, and urged France to boost cooperation.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] President of the European Commission Ursula von der Leyen told CNN that "one of our member states has been treated in a way that is not acceptable. ...
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] We want to know what happened and why." The EU also demanded an apology from Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] President of the European Council Charles Michel denounced a "lack of transparency and loyalty" by the US.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] The EU said the crisis affects the whole union.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] Preparations for a new EU-US trade and technology council between the US and EU were postponed.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] France eventually dropped their opposition to these talks which took place in Pittsburgh on 29 September 2021.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] France also attempted to delay the free trade talks between the EU and Australia.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] Key advocates for the TTC talks included EU's digital chief Margrethe Vestager, who favors open markets, and EU trade chief Valdis Dombrovskis from Latvia, who views the US alliance and NATO as a vital counterweight to Russia and China.
[src:ancient-greece/aukus-p02] Lithuanian deputy European Affairs Minister Arnoldas Prankevicius proclaimed "What is important is to keep trans-Atlantic unity, because we believe this is our biggest strength and biggest value, especially vis-à-vis such countries as Russia and China".
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] The organization's vision and mission, objectives, strategies and guiding principles, and Structure are presented on the AUSCANNZUKUS Information Portal.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] To produce products and processes to achieve Maritime C4 interoperability.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] To increase external sharing and understanding of AUSCANNZUKUS.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] Identify C4 interoperability requirements and risks.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] Identify, develop and utilize new technologies.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] Exchange information on national C4 capabilities, plans, and projects.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] To improve national awareness of AUSCANNZUKUS.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] Leverage exercises, experiments and demonstrations to deliver capability.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] Inform and influence multi national defence fora.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] All knowledge-sharing initiatives are to aim at providing innovative options, which are affordable to all AUSCANNZUKUS navies.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] All relevant information is to be shared with appropriate joint and combined organizations.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] The current AUSCANNZUKUS organization consists of the supervisory board, C4 Committee, and various other subordinate groups.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] Early in World War II communications interoperability between Allied forces was poor.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] During March 1941 the first high-level proposals to formally structure combined operations between the United States and the United Kingdom were considered; these discussions were the genesis of the current Combined Communications Electronics Board (CCEB).
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] The origins of the AUSCANNZUKUS organization arose from dialogue between Admiral Arleigh Burke, USN, and Admiral Lord Louis Mountbatten, RN, in 1960.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] Their intention was to align naval communications policies and prevent, or at least limit, any barriers to interoperability, with the imminent introduction of sophisticated new communications equipment.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] AUSCANNZUKUS matured to the current five-nation organization in 1980 when New Zealand became a full member.
[src:ancient-greece/auscannzukus] The organization's remit has expanded over the years, and its mission now includes fostering knowledge sharing and C4 interoperability between the navies of the five nations in order to increase operational effectiveness.
